-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-003.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-003.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,59 @@\n+# Iteration 3: Current-Scale Economics and Evidence Quality\n+\n+## Focus\n+\n+Determine whether the persistent path's present benefits justify its recurring lifecycle and maintenance burden, separating measured evidence from plausible benefit.\n+\n+## Findings\n+\n+1. The legacy path has a real asymptotic and I/O cost: it can rebuild disposable in-memory FTS by reading every eligible `DESIGN.md` (up to 64 KiB each), with fallback scan bounds of 1,290 records or 24 MiB. The styles tree is about 135 MiB locally. Persistent reads avoid this corpus walk. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:18-23] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:81-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:146-184] [SOURCE: command `du -sk .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles`: 138412 KiB]\n+2. The only direct adapter speed gate proves merely that persistent is faster on a synthetic 20-style fixture. It records no committed latency, ratio, warm/cold state, or current 1,290-style result. This supports directionality, not materiality. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/__tests__/adapter.test.mjs:107-132]\n+3. The strongest correctness evidence is excellent but orthogonal to default-path value: 69 tests cover atomic publication, telemetry, full-matrix oracle replay, and 1x/10x/100x determinism. They prove that the system can be operated safely, not that current callers need its capabilities or that end-to-end latency crosses an SLO. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:50-57] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:101-111]\n+4. Product-quality evidence is explicitly incomplete: there is no active published generation or embedding profile in the workspace; broad positive query shapes often admit all 1,290 bundles; relevance labels are authored/silver seed data rather than human gold; and live-corpus stage/SLO evidence remains open. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:38-44] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:117-123]\n+5. Current-scale benefit is therefore narrow but credible: lower repeat-query I/O/latency and stable immutable snapshots. Advanced vector, cursor, multimodal, and growth benefits are future options, not present requirements; the roadmap itself gates native/growth work on measured SLO or 10x-100x scale. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/spec.md:40-63] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:77-95]\n+6. Keeping SQLite as default creates recurring obligations independent of its small source footprint: generate and publish on corpus changes, distribute or bootstrap generations, retain rollback artifacts, migrate schema, monitor/repair vectors, diagnose pointer/generation failures, and keep dual parity during rollout. Those are operational state surfaces that the flat-file default does not currently own. [INFERENCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-87 and iteration 2]\n+7. At observed scale and evidence, the value case has not cleared a default-path threshold. This is not evidence that SQLite is slow or broken; it is negative knowledge that the missing workload, relevance, and lifecycle evidence makes permanent default ownership unjustified now. [INFERENCE: findings 1-6]\n+\n+## Ruled Out\n+\n+- Using the 20-style timing test as a production business case.\n+- Counting the 69-test correctness suite as proof of caller demand.\n+- Charging the whole 135 MiB corpus as database overhead; the database projection size is unknown because no real generation exists.\n+\n+## Dead Ends\n+\n+- Exact cost modeling is impossible without a real build artifact, build telemetry, query frequency, and representative p50/p95 traces.\n+\n+## Edge Cases\n+\n+- Ambiguous input: maintenance cost could be low if corpus updates are rare and DB generation is committed; no ownership or cadence evidence confirms that assumption.\n+- Contradictory evidence: persistent is directionally faster, yet the default-path recommendation can still be \"not now\" because materiality and operations are unproven.\n+- Missing dependencies: real database size/build time, production query frequency, current-scale latency, and human relevance judgments.\n+- Partial success: a qualitative economic decision is possible; a numerical ROI is not.\n+\n+## Sources Consulted\n+\n+- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/__tests__/adapter.test.mjs:1-132`\n+- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:1-238`\n+- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:1-126`\n+- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:1-283`\n+- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/spec.md:1-73`\n+- Local read-only size measurement of the styles, `_db`, and `_engine` trees.\n+\n+## Assessment\n+\n+- New information ratio: 0.72\n+- Novelty justification: Four findings are new economic evidence, two synthesize prior architecture facts, and one is a new negative-knowledge conclusion.\n+- Questions addressed: measurable benefits and recurring costs.\n+- Questions answered: repeat-query efficiency is plausible and directionally proven, but materiality and product value are not; default ownership is not justified by current evidence.\n+- Confidence: high on evidence gaps and legacy I/O shape; medium on operational cost magnitude.\n+\n+## Reflection\n+\n+- What worked and why: distinguishing correctness, performance direction, performance materiality, and product demand prevented sunk-cost reasoning.\n+- What did not work and why: no committed full-corpus DB exists, so exact size/build/query measurements could not be gathered without violating the research-only scope.\n+- What I would do differently: encode explicit promotion thresholds so a future decision can be evidence-driven rather than permanent.\n+\n+## Recommended Next Focus\n+\n+Build a weighted decision framework with present-state scoring and reversible promotion gates, then test whether shelving or wiring best fits those scores.\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-003.jsonl\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-003.jsonl\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-003.jsonl\n@@ -0,0 +1,4 @@\n+{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":3,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":3,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Current-scale economics and evidence quality\",\"findingsCount\":7,\"newInfoRatio\":0.72,\"noveltyJustification\":\"Four findings are new economic evidence, two synthesize prior architecture facts, and one is a new negative-knowledge conclusion.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Use a 20-style directional timing assertion as a production business case\",\"Treat correctness tests as proof of product demand\",\"Assume feature richness repays operational ownership\"],\"focusTrack\":\"economics\",\"edgeCase\":\"missing-dependency\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Glob\",\"Bash\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"adapter.test.mjs\",\"rank-fts.mjs\",\"015 foundation implementation-summary.md\",\"013 research.md\",\"015 parent spec.md\",\"du size measurement\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:00Z\",\"durationMs\":205000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-benefit-directional\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Persistent selection is directionally faster, but current-scale materiality is unmeasured.\"}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-evidence-gap\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"No published generation, active profile, workload trace, full-corpus timing, or human relevance set exists.\"}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-default-not-cleared\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Present evidence does not clear a threshold for permanent default-path ownership.\"}\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\n@@ -4,4 +4,7 @@\n {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":1,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":1,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Actual design-mode consumer contract and runtime path\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":1.0,\"noveltyJustification\":\"First iteration established five new contract-level findings from the actual consumers.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What contract and workload do the four design-mode corpus consumers require?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What contract and workload do the four design-mode corpus consumers require?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Consumer modules require a database-specific API\",\"SQLite would become the authoritative content store\",\"Consumer rewrites are required for backend selection\"],\"focusTrack\":\"architecture\",\"edgeCase\":\"ambiguous-input\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"styles/_engine/style-library.mjs\",\"design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs\",\"design-motion/corpus/motion-evidence.mjs\",\"design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs\",\"design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:38:00Z\",\"durationMs\":155000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":1,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:38:01Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":2,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":2,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Persistent backend readiness and missing default-path wiring\",\"findingsCount\":6,\"newInfoRatio\":0.85,\"noveltyJustification\":\"Five findings are new and one refines the consumer-demand result from iteration 1.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"The persistent database is only a stub\",\"Changing the adapter default is a complete cutover plan\",\"Implemented capabilities alone prove default-path value\"],\"focusTrack\":\"architecture\",\"edgeCase\":\"missing-dependency\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"styles/_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs\",\"styles/_db/README.md\",\"styles/_db/indexer.mjs\",\"styles/_db/schema.mjs\",\"styles/_db/retrieval.mjs\",\"styles/_db/operator.mjs\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:41:30Z\",\"durationMs\":208000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":2,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:41:31Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n+{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":3,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":3,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Current-scale economics and evidence quality\",\"findingsCount\":7,\"newInfoRatio\":0.72,\"noveltyJustification\":\"Four findings are new economic evidence, two synthesize prior architecture facts, and one is a new negative-knowledge conclusion.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Use a 20-style directional timing assertion as a production business case\",\"Treat correctness tests as proof of product demand\",\"Assume feature richness repays operational ownership\"],\"focusTrack\":\"economics\",\"edgeCase\":\"missing-dependency\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Glob\",\"Bash\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"adapter.test.mjs\",\"rank-fts.mjs\",\"015 foundation implementation-summary.md\",\"013 research.md\",\"015 parent spec.md\",\"du size measurement\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:00Z\",\"durationMs\":205000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n+{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"min_iterations_guard_pass\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":4,\"iterationCount\":3,\"minIterations\":3,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:01Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n+{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":3,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:01Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n@@ -21,9 +21,9 @@\n ## 4. Key Questions (Remaining)\n \n - [x] What contract and workload do design-interface, design-motion, design-audit, and design-foundations actually require from the styles library?\n - [x] How complete is the persistent implementation, and what exact work remains to make it the default and populate a real database?\n-- [ ] What measurable benefits justify SQLite at the present corpus size, and what recurring operational costs would default persistence introduce?\n+- [x] What measurable benefits justify SQLite at the present corpus size, and what recurring operational costs would default persistence introduce?\n - [ ] Which decision criteria and thresholds should govern keep versus shelve?\n - [ ] What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans, including rollback and preservation of useful evidence assets?\n <!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n \n@@ -31,23 +31,26 @@\n ## 5. Answered Questions\n \n - The four consumers require a bounded, generation-safe `runQuery`/`runHydrate` facade and degrade safely when retrieval is unavailable; none requires SQLite specifically. (iteration 1)\n - The persistent implementation is mature, but a real default requires a published initial generation plus explicit build/distribution/refresh/repair ownership and live cutover evidence. (iteration 2)\n+- Persistent selection avoids substantial repeat-query corpus I/O, but the only direct speed assertion is a 20-style fixture; present-scale materiality, workload demand, relevance quality, and lifecycle cost remain unmeasured. (iteration 3)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n \n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n <!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n ## 6. What Worked\n \n - Consumer-to-facade tracing: showed that backend choice is isolated below all four corpus modules. (iteration 1)\n - Implementation-versus-integration separation: distinguished mature database code from the absent operational lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n+- Evidence-class separation: distinguished correctness, directional speed, material speed, and product demand. (iteration 3)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n ## 7. What Failed\n \n - Initial wildcard include search: returned no files because the path/include shape was too broad; replaced with an exact call-site search. (iteration 1)\n - First-segment indexer read: did not reach the build function, so operator and README evidence were used to triangulate the published lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n+- Exact ROI modeling: blocked by the absent full-corpus database, workload trace, build timing, and human relevance set. (iteration 3)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n ## 8. Exhausted Approaches\n@@ -55,8 +58,10 @@\n - Database-specific consumer rewrites: ruled out because all consumers already call the adapter-backed facade. (iteration 1)\n - SQLite as authoritative content storage: ruled out because hydration remains flat-file artifact access. (iteration 1)\n - Default flip without build/distribution: ruled out because clean checkouts have no pointer or generation file. (iteration 2)\n - Capability inventory as business justification: ruled out because consumer demand and measured value are separate. (iteration 2)\n+- Synthetic 20-style timing as production justification: ruled out because it proves direction but records no materiality. (iteration 3)\n+- Correctness suite as demand proof: ruled out because safety and usefulness are separate questions. (iteration 3)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n ## 9. Ruled-Out Directions\n@@ -72,9 +77,9 @@\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n ## 11. Next Focus\n \n-Quantify benefits and recurring costs at the current corpus scale, including the limits of existing benchmark and relevance evidence.\n+Construct and score a reversible decision framework with explicit promotion gates for wiring versus shelving.\n <!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n \n ## 12. Known Context\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n@@ -1,35 +1,40 @@\n {\n   \"openQuestions\": [\n-    {\"id\":\"q-economics\",\"text\":\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\",\"status\":\"open\"},\n     {\"id\":\"q-criteria\",\"text\":\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\",\"status\":\"open\"},\n     {\"id\":\"q-plans\",\"text\":\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\",\"status\":\"open\"}\n   ],\n   \"resolvedQuestions\": [\n     {\"id\":\"q-consumers\",\"text\":\"What contract and workload do the four design-mode corpus consumers require?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":1,\"answer\":\"A bounded generation-safe query/hydration facade; no consumer requires SQLite specifically.\"},\n-    {\"id\":\"q-readiness\",\"text\":\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":2,\"answer\":\"Technically mature, but missing a published artifact and an owned build/distribution/refresh/repair lifecycle plus live cutover evidence.\"}\n+    {\"id\":\"q-readiness\",\"text\":\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":2,\"answer\":\"Technically mature, but missing a published artifact and an owned build/distribution/refresh/repair lifecycle plus live cutover evidence.\"},\n+    {\"id\":\"q-economics\",\"text\":\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":3,\"answer\":\"It credibly removes repeat-query corpus I/O, but current-scale materiality and demand are unmeasured while defaulting introduces permanent publication, freshness, migration, monitoring, and repair ownership.\"}\n   ],\n   \"keyFindings\": [\n     {\"id\":\"f-consumer-facade\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"All four corpus modules use the storage-neutral runQuery/runHydrate facade.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:181-207\",\"four corpus modules\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-content-authority\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Flat artifacts remain authoritative content under persistent selection.\",\"sources\":[\"consumer hydration calls\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-legacy-freshness-cost\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Legacy queries rebuild and compare the live corpus manifest on every call.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:123-159\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-db-mature\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"The persistent projection and operator machinery are technically mature.\",\"sources\":[\"schema.mjs:35-269\",\"retrieval.mjs:364-510\",\"operator.mjs:75-247\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-lifecycle-unowned\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"No default build, distribution, refresh, or repair owner exists.\",\"sources\":[\"README.md:40-49\",\"operator.mjs:213-226\"]},\n-    {\"id\":\"f-shadow-bounded\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Shadow parity tolerates ranking and identity differences and is not a sufficient cutover gate alone.\",\"sources\":[\"persistent-adapter.mjs:113-141\"]}\n+    {\"id\":\"f-shadow-bounded\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Shadow parity tolerates ranking and identity differences and is not a sufficient cutover gate alone.\",\"sources\":[\"persistent-adapter.mjs:113-141\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-benefit-directional\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Persistent selection is directionally faster, but current-scale materiality is unmeasured.\",\"sources\":[\"adapter.test.mjs:107-132\",\"rank-fts.mjs:81-184\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-evidence-gap\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"No published generation, active profile, workload trace, full-corpus timing, or human relevance set exists.\",\"sources\":[\"013 research.md:38-44\",\"foundation implementation-summary.md:117-123\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-default-not-cleared\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Present evidence does not clear a threshold for permanent default-path ownership.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-003.md\"]}\n   ],\n   \"ruledOutDirections\": [\n     {\"approach\":\"Rewrite consumers for a database API\",\"reason\":\"The existing facade already isolates backend selection.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Move authoritative content into SQLite\",\"reason\":\"Consumer hydration semantics rely on bounded flat artifacts.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Flip the adapter default without publishing and owning the database lifecycle\",\"reason\":\"Clean checkouts have no generation pointer and reads correctly fail closed.\",\"iterations\":[2]},\n-    {\"approach\":\"Use feature richness as proof of value\",\"reason\":\"Implemented supply does not establish observed consumer demand.\",\"iterations\":[2]}\n+    {\"approach\":\"Use feature richness as proof of value\",\"reason\":\"Implemented supply does not establish observed consumer demand.\",\"iterations\":[2]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Promote based on the 20-style timing assertion\",\"reason\":\"It proves directionality but records no current-scale materiality.\",\"iterations\":[3]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Treat correctness coverage as product demand\",\"reason\":\"Safety evidence does not establish workload value.\",\"iterations\":[3]}\n   ],\n   \"metrics\": {\n-    \"iterationsCompleted\": 2,\n-    \"openQuestions\": 3,\n-    \"resolvedQuestions\": 2,\n-    \"keyFindings\": 6,\n+    \"iterationsCompleted\": 3,\n+    \"openQuestions\": 2,\n+    \"resolvedQuestions\": 3,\n+    \"keyFindings\": 9,\n     \"convergenceScore\": 0.0,\n-    \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":11,\"spec\":0,\"tests\":0}\n+    \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":13,\"spec\":3,\"tests\":2,\"measurement\":1}\n   },\n   \"status\": \"iterating\",\n   \"sessionId\": \"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\n   \"generation\": 1\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n@@ -5,25 +5,29 @@\n | Run | Focus | newInfoRatio | Findings | Status |\n |---:|---|---:|---:|---|\n | 1 | Consumer contract and runtime path | 1.00 | 5 | complete |\n | 2 | Persistent readiness and missing wiring | 0.85 | 6 | complete |\n+| 3 | Current-scale economics and evidence | 0.72 | 7 | complete |\n \n ## Question Status\n \n-- 2/5 answered; 3 remaining.\n-- Answered: consumer contract; persistent readiness and missing wiring.\n+- 3/5 answered; 2 remaining.\n+- Answered: consumer contract; persistent readiness; current-scale economics.\n \n ## Convergence Trend\n \n-- Ratios: 1.00 -> 0.85 (descending, still high novelty)\n+- Ratios: 1.00 -> 0.85 -> 0.72 (descending, still above convergence threshold)\n+- Minimum iteration floor cleared. Stop remains disabled until run 5 by policy.\n - Stop policy: max-iterations; convergence is telemetry until run 5.\n \n ## Dead Ends\n \n - Database-specific consumer rewrites.\n - SQLite as authoritative content storage.\n - Default flip without a publication lifecycle.\n - Feature richness as proof of value.\n+- Synthetic fixture speed as a production business case.\n+- Correctness tests as proof of demand.\n \n ## Next Focus\n \n-Economic case at current scale and limits of benchmark/relevance evidence.\n+Weighted decision framework and reversible promotion gates.\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n@@ -17,4 +17,12 @@\n \n ## Open Decision\n \n Whether that avoidable per-query work and future retrieval capabilities outweigh build/publication/repair complexity at a 1,290-style corpus.\n+\n+## Evidence Quality\n+\n+The economic evidence does not presently support defaulting. Legacy retrieval performs substantial repeated I/O, and persistent mode is directionally faster, but only a synthetic 20-style assertion exists. There is no published full-corpus generation, workload trace, current-scale p50/p95, active vector profile, or human relevance set. Correctness is well proven; material value is not. [SOURCE: iteration-003.md]\n+\n+## Provisional Verdict\n+\n+Favor formal shelving as the current default decision, with objective reactivation gates. This avoids turning an unmeasured projection into a permanent operational dependency while preserving a path to promote it if real workload evidence clears the bar.\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log\n@@ -1,3 +1,4 @@\n {\"event\":\"started\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:35:19Z\",\"duration_ms\":0,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":0,\"elapsed_ms\":0,\"score\":0}}\n {\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:38:01Z\",\"duration_ms\":162000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":1,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":1,\"elapsed_ms\":162000,\"score\":1.0}}\n {\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:41:31Z\",\"duration_ms\":372000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":2,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":2,\"elapsed_ms\":372000,\"score\":0.85}}\n+{\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:01Z\",\"duration_ms\":582000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":3,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":3,\"elapsed_ms\":582000,\"score\":0.72}}\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-003.md","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-003.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-003.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-003.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-003.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,7 @@\n+DEEP-RESEARCH ITERATION 3\n+\n+STATE SUMMARY: Iteration 3 of 5; 2/5 questions answered; ratios 1.00 -> 0.85; stop policy is max-iterations.\n+\n+Focus Area: Benefit, cost, and evidence quality at the current corpus scale.\n+Constraint: Treat convergence as telemetry only and broaden rather than synthesize early.\n+Route: mode=research; target_agent=deep-research; execution=single_iteration; state_source=externalized_files.\n","additions":7,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-003.md","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-003.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-003.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-003.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-003.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,59 @@\n+# Iteration 3: Current-Scale Economics and Evidence Quality\n+\n+## Focus\n+\n+Determine whether the persistent path's present benefits justify its recurring lifecycle and maintenance burden, separating measured evidence from plausible benefit.\n+\n+## Findings\n+\n+1. The legacy path has a real asymptotic and I/O cost: it can rebuild disposable in-memory FTS by reading every eligible `DESIGN.md` (up to 64 KiB each), with fallback scan bounds of 1,290 records or 24 MiB. The styles tree is about 135 MiB locally. Persistent reads avoid this corpus walk. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:18-23] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:81-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:146-184] [SOURCE: command `du -sk .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles`: 138412 KiB]\n+2. The only direct adapter speed gate proves merely that persistent is faster on a synthetic 20-style fixture. It records no committed latency, ratio, warm/cold state, or current 1,290-style result. This supports directionality, not materiality. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/__tests__/adapter.test.mjs:107-132]\n+3. The strongest correctness evidence is excellent but orthogonal to default-path value: 69 tests cover atomic publication, telemetry, full-matrix oracle replay, and 1x/10x/100x determinism. They prove that the system can be operated safely, not that current callers need its capabilities or that end-to-end latency crosses an SLO. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:50-57] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:101-111]\n+4. Product-quality evidence is explicitly incomplete: there is no active published generation or embedding profile in the workspace; broad positive query shapes often admit all 1,290 bundles; relevance labels are authored/silver seed data rather than human gold; and live-corpus stage/SLO evidence remains open. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:38-44] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:117-123]\n+5. Current-scale benefit is therefore narrow but credible: lower repeat-query I/O/latency and stable immutable snapshots. Advanced vector, cursor, multimodal, and growth benefits are future options, not present requirements; the roadmap itself gates native/growth work on measured SLO or 10x-100x scale. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/spec.md:40-63] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:77-95]\n+6. Keeping SQLite as default creates recurring obligations independent of its small source footprint: generate and publish on corpus changes, distribute or bootstrap generations, retain rollback artifacts, migrate schema, monitor/repair vectors, diagnose pointer/generation failures, and keep dual parity during rollout. Those are operational state surfaces that the flat-file default does not currently own. [INFERENCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-87 and iteration 2]\n+7. At observed scale and evidence, the value case has not cleared a default-path threshold. This is not evidence that SQLite is slow or broken; it is negative knowledge that the missing workload, relevance, and lifecycle evidence makes permanent default ownership unjustified now. [INFERENCE: findings 1-6]\n+\n+## Ruled Out\n+\n+- Using the 20-style timing test as a production business case.\n+- Counting the 69-test correctness suite as proof of caller demand.\n+- Charging the whole 135 MiB corpus as database overhead; the database projection size is unknown because no real generation exists.\n+\n+## Dead Ends\n+\n+- Exact cost modeling is impossible without a real build artifact, build telemetry, query frequency, and representative p50/p95 traces.\n+\n+## Edge Cases\n+\n+- Ambiguous input: maintenance cost could be low if corpus updates are rare and DB generation is committed; no ownership or cadence evidence confirms that assumption.\n+- Contradictory evidence: persistent is directionally faster, yet the default-path recommendation can still be \"not now\" because materiality and operations are unproven.\n+- Missing dependencies: real database size/build time, production query frequency, current-scale latency, and human relevance judgments.\n+- Partial success: a qualitative economic decision is possible; a numerical ROI is not.\n+\n+## Sources Consulted\n+\n+- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/__tests__/adapter.test.mjs:1-132`\n+- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:1-238`\n+- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:1-126`\n+- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:1-283`\n+- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/spec.md:1-73`\n+- Local read-only size measurement of the styles, `_db`, and `_engine` trees.\n+\n+## Assessment\n+\n+- New information ratio: 0.72\n+- Novelty justification: Four findings are new economic evidence, two synthesize prior architecture facts, and one is a new negative-knowledge conclusion.\n+- Questions addressed: measurable benefits and recurring costs.\n+- Questions answered: repeat-query efficiency is plausible and directionally proven, but materiality and product value are not; default ownership is not justified by current evidence.\n+- Confidence: high on evidence gaps and legacy I/O shape; medium on operational cost magnitude.\n+\n+## Reflection\n+\n+- What worked and why: distinguishing correctness, performance direction, performance materiality, and product demand prevented sunk-cost reasoning.\n+- What did not work and why: no committed full-corpus DB exists, so exact size/build/query measurements could not be gathered without violating the research-only scope.\n+- What I would do differently: encode explicit promotion thresholds so a future decision can be evidence-driven rather than permanent.\n+\n+## Recommended Next Focus\n+\n+Build a weighted decision framework with present-state scoring and reversible promotion gates, then test whether shelving or wiring best fits those scores.\n","additions":59,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-003.jsonl","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-003.jsonl","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-003.jsonl\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-003.jsonl\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-003.jsonl\n@@ -0,0 +1,4 @@\n+{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":3,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":3,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Current-scale economics and evidence quality\",\"findingsCount\":7,\"newInfoRatio\":0.72,\"noveltyJustification\":\"Four findings are new economic evidence, two synthesize prior architecture facts, and one is a new negative-knowledge conclusion.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Use a 20-style directional timing assertion as a production business case\",\"Treat correctness tests as proof of product demand\",\"Assume feature richness repays operational ownership\"],\"focusTrack\":\"economics\",\"edgeCase\":\"missing-dependency\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Glob\",\"Bash\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"adapter.test.mjs\",\"rank-fts.mjs\",\"015 foundation implementation-summary.md\",\"013 research.md\",\"015 parent spec.md\",\"du size measurement\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:00Z\",\"durationMs\":205000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-benefit-directional\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Persistent selection is directionally faster, but current-scale materiality is unmeasured.\"}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-evidence-gap\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"No published generation, active profile, workload trace, full-corpus timing, or human relevance set exists.\"}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-default-not-cleared\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Present evidence does not clear a threshold for permanent default-path ownership.\"}\n","additions":4,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl","type":"update","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\n@@ -4,4 +4,7 @@\n {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":1,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":1,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Actual design-mode consumer contract and runtime path\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":1.0,\"noveltyJustification\":\"First iteration established five new contract-level findings from the actual consumers.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What contract and workload do the four design-mode corpus consumers require?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What contract and workload do the four design-mode corpus consumers require?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Consumer modules require a database-specific API\",\"SQLite would become the authoritative content store\",\"Consumer rewrites are required for backend selection\"],\"focusTrack\":\"architecture\",\"edgeCase\":\"ambiguous-input\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"styles/_engine/style-library.mjs\",\"design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs\",\"design-motion/corpus/motion-evidence.mjs\",\"design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs\",\"design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:38:00Z\",\"durationMs\":155000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":1,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:38:01Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":2,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":2,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Persistent backend readiness and missing default-path wiring\",\"findingsCount\":6,\"newInfoRatio\":0.85,\"noveltyJustification\":\"Five findings are new and one refines the consumer-demand result from iteration 1.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"The persistent database is only a stub\",\"Changing the adapter default is a complete cutover plan\",\"Implemented capabilities alone prove default-path value\"],\"focusTrack\":\"architecture\",\"edgeCase\":\"missing-dependency\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"styles/_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs\",\"styles/_db/README.md\",\"styles/_db/indexer.mjs\",\"styles/_db/schema.mjs\",\"styles/_db/retrieval.mjs\",\"styles/_db/operator.mjs\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:41:30Z\",\"durationMs\":208000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":2,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:41:31Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n+{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":3,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":3,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Current-scale economics and evidence quality\",\"findingsCount\":7,\"newInfoRatio\":0.72,\"noveltyJustification\":\"Four findings are new economic evidence, two synthesize prior architecture facts, and one is a new negative-knowledge conclusion.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Use a 20-style directional timing assertion as a production business case\",\"Treat correctness tests as proof of product demand\",\"Assume feature richness repays operational ownership\"],\"focusTrack\":\"economics\",\"edgeCase\":\"missing-dependency\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Glob\",\"Bash\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"adapter.test.mjs\",\"rank-fts.mjs\",\"015 foundation implementation-summary.md\",\"013 research.md\",\"015 parent spec.md\",\"du size measurement\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:00Z\",\"durationMs\":205000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n+{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"min_iterations_guard_pass\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":4,\"iterationCount\":3,\"minIterations\":3,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:01Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n+{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":3,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:01Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n","additions":3,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md","type":"update","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n@@ -21,9 +21,9 @@\n ## 4. Key Questions (Remaining)\n \n - [x] What contract and workload do design-interface, design-motion, design-audit, and design-foundations actually require from the styles library?\n - [x] How complete is the persistent implementation, and what exact work remains to make it the default and populate a real database?\n-- [ ] What measurable benefits justify SQLite at the present corpus size, and what recurring operational costs would default persistence introduce?\n+- [x] What measurable benefits justify SQLite at the present corpus size, and what recurring operational costs would default persistence introduce?\n - [ ] Which decision criteria and thresholds should govern keep versus shelve?\n - [ ] What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans, including rollback and preservation of useful evidence assets?\n <!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n \n@@ -31,23 +31,26 @@\n ## 5. Answered Questions\n \n - The four consumers require a bounded, generation-safe `runQuery`/`runHydrate` facade and degrade safely when retrieval is unavailable; none requires SQLite specifically. (iteration 1)\n - The persistent implementation is mature, but a real default requires a published initial generation plus explicit build/distribution/refresh/repair ownership and live cutover evidence. (iteration 2)\n+- Persistent selection avoids substantial repeat-query corpus I/O, but the only direct speed assertion is a 20-style fixture; present-scale materiality, workload demand, relevance quality, and lifecycle cost remain unmeasured. (iteration 3)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n \n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n <!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n ## 6. What Worked\n \n - Consumer-to-facade tracing: showed that backend choice is isolated below all four corpus modules. (iteration 1)\n - Implementation-versus-integration separation: distinguished mature database code from the absent operational lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n+- Evidence-class separation: distinguished correctness, directional speed, material speed, and product demand. (iteration 3)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n ## 7. What Failed\n \n - Initial wildcard include search: returned no files because the path/include shape was too broad; replaced with an exact call-site search. (iteration 1)\n - First-segment indexer read: did not reach the build function, so operator and README evidence were used to triangulate the published lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n+- Exact ROI modeling: blocked by the absent full-corpus database, workload trace, build timing, and human relevance set. (iteration 3)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n ## 8. Exhausted Approaches\n@@ -55,8 +58,10 @@\n - Database-specific consumer rewrites: ruled out because all consumers already call the adapter-backed facade. (iteration 1)\n - SQLite as authoritative content storage: ruled out because hydration remains flat-file artifact access. (iteration 1)\n - Default flip without build/distribution: ruled out because clean checkouts have no pointer or generation file. (iteration 2)\n - Capability inventory as business justification: ruled out because consumer demand and measured value are separate. (iteration 2)\n+- Synthetic 20-style timing as production justification: ruled out because it proves direction but records no materiality. (iteration 3)\n+- Correctness suite as demand proof: ruled out because safety and usefulness are separate questions. (iteration 3)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n ## 9. Ruled-Out Directions\n@@ -72,9 +77,9 @@\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n ## 11. Next Focus\n \n-Quantify benefits and recurring costs at the current corpus scale, including the limits of existing benchmark and relevance evidence.\n+Construct and score a reversible decision framework with explicit promotion gates for wiring versus shelving.\n <!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n \n ## 12. Known Context\n","additions":7,"deletions":2},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json","type":"update","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n@@ -1,35 +1,40 @@\n {\n   \"openQuestions\": [\n-    {\"id\":\"q-economics\",\"text\":\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\",\"status\":\"open\"},\n     {\"id\":\"q-criteria\",\"text\":\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\",\"status\":\"open\"},\n     {\"id\":\"q-plans\",\"text\":\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\",\"status\":\"open\"}\n   ],\n   \"resolvedQuestions\": [\n     {\"id\":\"q-consumers\",\"text\":\"What contract and workload do the four design-mode corpus consumers require?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":1,\"answer\":\"A bounded generation-safe query/hydration facade; no consumer requires SQLite specifically.\"},\n-    {\"id\":\"q-readiness\",\"text\":\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":2,\"answer\":\"Technically mature, but missing a published artifact and an owned build/distribution/refresh/repair lifecycle plus live cutover evidence.\"}\n+    {\"id\":\"q-readiness\",\"text\":\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":2,\"answer\":\"Technically mature, but missing a published artifact and an owned build/distribution/refresh/repair lifecycle plus live cutover evidence.\"},\n+    {\"id\":\"q-economics\",\"text\":\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":3,\"answer\":\"It credibly removes repeat-query corpus I/O, but current-scale materiality and demand are unmeasured while defaulting introduces permanent publication, freshness, migration, monitoring, and repair ownership.\"}\n   ],\n   \"keyFindings\": [\n     {\"id\":\"f-consumer-facade\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"All four corpus modules use the storage-neutral runQuery/runHydrate facade.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:181-207\",\"four corpus modules\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-content-authority\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Flat artifacts remain authoritative content under persistent selection.\",\"sources\":[\"consumer hydration calls\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-legacy-freshness-cost\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Legacy queries rebuild and compare the live corpus manifest on every call.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:123-159\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-db-mature\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"The persistent projection and operator machinery are technically mature.\",\"sources\":[\"schema.mjs:35-269\",\"retrieval.mjs:364-510\",\"operator.mjs:75-247\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-lifecycle-unowned\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"No default build, distribution, refresh, or repair owner exists.\",\"sources\":[\"README.md:40-49\",\"operator.mjs:213-226\"]},\n-    {\"id\":\"f-shadow-bounded\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Shadow parity tolerates ranking and identity differences and is not a sufficient cutover gate alone.\",\"sources\":[\"persistent-adapter.mjs:113-141\"]}\n+    {\"id\":\"f-shadow-bounded\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Shadow parity tolerates ranking and identity differences and is not a sufficient cutover gate alone.\",\"sources\":[\"persistent-adapter.mjs:113-141\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-benefit-directional\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Persistent selection is directionally faster, but current-scale materiality is unmeasured.\",\"sources\":[\"adapter.test.mjs:107-132\",\"rank-fts.mjs:81-184\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-evidence-gap\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"No published generation, active profile, workload trace, full-corpus timing, or human relevance set exists.\",\"sources\":[\"013 research.md:38-44\",\"foundation implementation-summary.md:117-123\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-default-not-cleared\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Present evidence does not clear a threshold for permanent default-path ownership.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-003.md\"]}\n   ],\n   \"ruledOutDirections\": [\n     {\"approach\":\"Rewrite consumers for a database API\",\"reason\":\"The existing facade already isolates backend selection.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Move authoritative content into SQLite\",\"reason\":\"Consumer hydration semantics rely on bounded flat artifacts.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Flip the adapter default without publishing and owning the database lifecycle\",\"reason\":\"Clean checkouts have no generation pointer and reads correctly fail closed.\",\"iterations\":[2]},\n-    {\"approach\":\"Use feature richness as proof of value\",\"reason\":\"Implemented supply does not establish observed consumer demand.\",\"iterations\":[2]}\n+    {\"approach\":\"Use feature richness as proof of value\",\"reason\":\"Implemented supply does not establish observed consumer demand.\",\"iterations\":[2]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Promote based on the 20-style timing assertion\",\"reason\":\"It proves directionality but records no current-scale materiality.\",\"iterations\":[3]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Treat correctness coverage as product demand\",\"reason\":\"Safety evidence does not establish workload value.\",\"iterations\":[3]}\n   ],\n   \"metrics\": {\n-    \"iterationsCompleted\": 2,\n-    \"openQuestions\": 3,\n-    \"resolvedQuestions\": 2,\n-    \"keyFindings\": 6,\n+    \"iterationsCompleted\": 3,\n+    \"openQuestions\": 2,\n+    \"resolvedQuestions\": 3,\n+    \"keyFindings\": 9,\n     \"convergenceScore\": 0.0,\n-    \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":11,\"spec\":0,\"tests\":0}\n+    \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":13,\"spec\":3,\"tests\":2,\"measurement\":1}\n   },\n   \"status\": \"iterating\",\n   \"sessionId\": \"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\n   \"generation\": 1\n","additions":14,"deletions":9},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md","type":"update","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n@@ -5,25 +5,29 @@\n | Run | Focus | newInfoRatio | Findings | Status |\n |---:|---|---:|---:|---|\n | 1 | Consumer contract and runtime path | 1.00 | 5 | complete |\n | 2 | Persistent readiness and missing wiring | 0.85 | 6 | complete |\n+| 3 | Current-scale economics and evidence | 0.72 | 7 | complete |\n \n ## Question Status\n \n-- 2/5 answered; 3 remaining.\n-- Answered: consumer contract; persistent readiness and missing wiring.\n+- 3/5 answered; 2 remaining.\n+- Answered: consumer contract; persistent readiness; current-scale economics.\n \n ## Convergence Trend\n \n-- Ratios: 1.00 -> 0.85 (descending, still high novelty)\n+- Ratios: 1.00 -> 0.85 -> 0.72 (descending, still above convergence threshold)\n+- Minimum iteration floor cleared. Stop remains disabled until run 5 by policy.\n - Stop policy: max-iterations; convergence is telemetry until run 5.\n \n ## Dead Ends\n \n - Database-specific consumer rewrites.\n - SQLite as authoritative content storage.\n - Default flip without a publication lifecycle.\n - Feature richness as proof of value.\n+- Synthetic fixture speed as a production business case.\n+- Correctness tests as proof of demand.\n \n ## Next Focus\n \n-Economic case at current scale and limits of benchmark/relevance evidence.\n+Weighted decision framework and reversible promotion gates.\n","additions":8,"deletions":4},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md","type":"update","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n@@ -17,4 +17,12 @@\n \n ## Open Decision\n \n Whether that avoidable per-query work and future retrieval capabilities outweigh build/publication/repair complexity at a 1,290-style corpus.\n+\n+## Evidence Quality\n+\n+The economic evidence does not presently support defaulting. Legacy retrieval performs substantial repeated I/O, and persistent mode is directionally faster, but only a synthetic 20-style assertion exists. There is no published full-corpus generation, workload trace, current-scale p50/p95, active vector profile, or human relevance set. Correctness is well proven; material value is not. [SOURCE: iteration-003.md]\n+\n+## Provisional Verdict\n+\n+Favor formal shelving as the current default decision, with objective reactivation gates. This avoids turning an unmeasured projection into a permanent operational dependency while preserving a path to promote it if real workload evidence clears the bar.\n","additions":8,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log","type":"update","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/rese