{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1784623549781,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"id":"prt_f83da4d52001eUUmb91mSRiwgQ","messageID":"msg_f83da3c73001aBOUrUtcHYsHi2","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","snapshot":"d31066f3e68fd124c50c33ec9119b2c4231a230b","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784623640412,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"apply_patch","callID":"call_KaNhFzWQ5Mk5uOqDLtqxBIum","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"patchText":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Add File: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-005.md\n+DEEP-RESEARCH ITERATION 5\n+\n+STATE SUMMARY: Iteration 5 of 5; 4/5 questions answered; ratios 1.00 -> 0.85 -> 0.72 -> 0.58.\n+\n+Focus Area: Adversarial validation and complete plans for both wiring and shelving.\n+Terminal rule: Complete this iteration, then stop with maxIterationsReached and enter synthesis.\n+Route: mode=research; target_agent=deep-research; execution=single_iteration; state_source=externalized_files.\n*** Add File: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md\n+# Iteration 5: Adversarial Validation and Both Execution Plans\n+\n+## Focus\n+\n+Try to overturn the shelf recommendation, map the live-code blast radius, and deliver complete reversible plans for either operator choice.\n+\n+## Findings\n+\n+1. Shelving has a bounded live-code blast radius. In executable `.mjs`, database-mode references outside `_db` occur only in `_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs`, `_engine/style-library.mjs`, and the DB adapter tests. The four corpus modules have no direct DB imports, so their API need not change. [SOURCE: scoped Grep for `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE|styleDatabaseMode|persistent-adapter|_db/...` under `.opencode/**/*.mjs`]\n+2. The flat engine is not an unsafe fallback. Its dedicated suite covers byte-stable non-writing checks, eligibility-first behavior, source-scan fallback, generation/path/hash hydration guards, invalidation, and proof behavior. It rejects poisoned derived fields and stale manifests before query, and enforces generation, rights, byte, and path-escape guards during hydration. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/index.mjs:1-10] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/check-stable.test.mjs:14-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/hydrate-guard.test.mjs:20-163]\n+3. The strongest pro-wire counterargument is repeat-query cost: the legacy engine reconstructs freshness and disposable search repeatedly, while the persistent implementation already has safe publication and richer retrieval. Wiring now would be rational if real design sessions issue enough queries to breach an approved latency SLO and a clean-checkout publication lifecycle is already funded. Neither condition is evidenced, so the counterargument does not overturn the recommendation. [SOURCE: iterations 1-3]\n+4. **Wiring plan if kept:** (a) preserve the facade and flat files as content authority; (b) choose and document clean-checkout distribution, either checked-in immutable generation under a size budget or mandatory install/prewarm build; (c) build and publish a real full-corpus generation, record size/build telemetry, and verify status/rollback; (d) add authoritative refresh ownership after corpus extraction plus periodic reconciliation; (e) run legacy/persistent shadow against representative consumer requests, strict oracle/refusal/generation parity, and human relevance judgments; (f) meet every promotion gate from iteration 4; (g) switch the adapter default to persistent while retaining an explicit legacy kill switch for a bounded observation window; (h) monitor pointer/generation/vector failures and latency; (i) remove dual-mode code only after the window. Rollback is one manifest-pointer reversal plus the legacy kill switch. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-87] [SOURCE: iteration-004.md]\n+5. **Deprecation plan if shelved:** (a) record the decision and mark the 015 roadmap and children superseded/shelved rather than planned; (b) retain 013/015/this research as design evidence and reactivation gates; (c) remove `_db`, DB-only tests/goldens/seeds, `persistent-adapter.mjs`, `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE`, `styleDatabaseMode`, CLI `--backend/--database`, and DB README claims; (d) route `runQuery`/`runHydrate` directly to the existing flat implementation; (e) keep the retrieval manifest because it is the flat engine's generation/freshness contract, then rename/restructure it only in the separate filesystem packet; (f) run the flat engine suite plus all four corpus suites and verify no DB imports/modes/artifacts remain; (g) remove planned DB evolution from active navigation. Rollback is a targeted Git revert; no data migration exists because no real DB was published. [SOURCE: scoped dependency Grep] [SOURCE: scoped retrieval-manifest Grep] [SOURCE: gap-analysis.md:72-105]\n+6. Preserving dormant runtime code is not a safe middle path. It leaves two supported semantics, mode-dependent failures, roadmap obligations, and documentation drift while providing no user-visible default capability. Preserve knowledge, not an unowned live surface. [INFERENCE: iterations 2-5]\n+\n+## Ruled Out\n+\n+- Shelf by deleting `_retrieval-manifest.json`: it belongs to and protects the flat engine.\n+- Shelf while leaving environment/CLI switches live: that is the current dormant state, not remediation.\n+- Wire by lazy query-time build: integrity-sensitive reads should not unexpectedly walk and mutate the corpus.\n+- Wire without a clean-checkout distribution decision: a missing pointer would make default consumers fail.\n+\n+## Dead Ends\n+\n+- No evidence overturns the shelf recommendation. The remaining pro-wire case is explicitly contingent on future measured workload and funded lifecycle ownership.\n+\n+## Edge Cases\n+\n+- Ambiguous input: whether to preserve generic canonicalizer/telemetry/oracle modules. They are currently DB-owned and have no independent consumer; preserve their design in docs/Git, not live source, unless a concrete reuse is identified before removal.\n+- Contradictory evidence: the recently built foundation is high quality, but removing it can still be correct because quality does not create demand.\n+- Missing dependencies: the operator must approve final deletion scope and the proposed numeric reactivation thresholds.\n+- Partial success: plans are implementation-ready at decision level but intentionally do not enumerate every deleted file.\n+\n+## Sources Consulted\n+\n+- Detached state/config/strategy through iteration 4.\n+- Scoped DB-mode/import dependency search.\n+- Scoped retrieval-manifest/build ownership search.\n+- Flat engine test index, stable-check tests, and hydration-guard tests.\n+\n+## Assessment\n+\n+- New information ratio: 0.43\n+- Novelty justification: The bounded blast radius and both sequenced execution plans are new; the final recommendation consolidates prior evidence.\n+- Questions addressed: safe wiring and deprecation plans.\n+- Questions answered: both paths are reversible; shelving is lower-risk and better supported now.\n+- Confidence: high on recommendation and blast radius; medium on exact implementation scope pending a dedicated plan/review.\n+\n+## Reflection\n+\n+- What worked and why: dependency search confirmed that storage choice is isolated enough for a clean shelf without consumer rewrites.\n+- What did not work and why: no runtime trace exists to test the strongest pro-wire hypothesis; it remains a reactivation gate.\n+- What I would do differently: if the operator chooses wire despite the recommendation, make the first implementation task measurement and distribution proof, not default flipping.\n+\n+## Recommended Next Focus\n+\n+Synthesize the five iterations into the final decision report. Stop reason: `maxIterationsReached`.\n*** Add File: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-005.jsonl\n+{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":5,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":5,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Adversarial validation and complete wire/shelf execution plans\",\"findingsCount\":6,\"newInfoRatio\":0.43,\"noveltyJustification\":\"The bounded blast radius and both sequenced execution plans are new; the final recommendation consolidates prior evidence.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Delete the flat retrieval manifest when shelving\",\"Leave database environment and CLI switches live after shelving\",\"Build the database lazily on query\",\"Wire without clean-checkout distribution ownership\",\"Keep dormant runtime as a compromise\"],\"focusTrack\":\"execution\",\"edgeCase\":\"contradictory-evidence\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"DB mode/import dependency search\",\"retrieval manifest ownership search\",\"engine test index\",\"check-stable.test.mjs\",\"hydrate-guard.test.mjs\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:40Z\",\"durationMs\":198000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-blast-radius\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"Executable DB coupling outside the DB tree is isolated to the adapter, facade, and adapter tests.\"}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-wire-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A safe wire plan begins with distribution, full-corpus measurement, refresh ownership, shadow/relevance gates, then bounded cutover.\"}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-shelf-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A formal shelf removes live DB modes/code and supersedes the roadmap while retaining the flat retrieval manifest and design evidence.\"}\n*** Update File: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\n@@\n {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":4,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:48:21Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n+{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":5,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":5,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Adversarial validation and complete wire/shelf execution plans\",\"findingsCount\":6,\"newInfoRatio\":0.43,\"noveltyJustification\":\"The bounded blast radius and both sequenced execution plans are new; the final recommendation consolidates prior evidence.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Delete the flat retrieval manifest when shelving\",\"Leave database environment and CLI switches live after shelving\",\"Build the database lazily on query\",\"Wire without clean-checkout distribution ownership\",\"Keep dormant runtime as a compromise\"],\"focusTrack\":\"execution\",\"edgeCase\":\"contradictory-evidence\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"DB mode/import dependency search\",\"retrieval manifest ownership search\",\"engine test index\",\"check-stable.test.mjs\",\"hydrate-guard.test.mjs\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:40Z\",\"durationMs\":198000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n+{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":5,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:41Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n+{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"max_iterations_reached\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":5,\"stopReason\":\"maxIterationsReached\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:41Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n*** Update File: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n@@\n-- [ ] What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans, including rollback and preservation of useful evidence assets?\n+- [x] What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans, including rollback and preservation of useful evidence assets?\n@@\n - A weighted present-state framework scores formal shelving 85/100 versus wiring 54/100; reversal requires conjunctive workload, materiality, lifecycle, parity, relevance, shadow, rollback, and demand gates. (iteration 4)\n+- Both paths are reversible: wiring requires distribution, build/refresh ownership, shadow/relevance gates, then cutover; shelving removes live DB code/modes and supersedes the roadmap while preserving the flat manifest and design evidence. (iteration 5)\n@@\n - Weighted scoring and sensitivity check: made judgment explicit and showed the result is not dependent on one criterion. (iteration 4)\n+- Dependency and manifest-ownership scans: bounded the shelf blast radius and protected the flat engine's retrieval manifest. (iteration 5)\n@@\n - Broad feature-token search: included database internals, so its absence claim was narrowed to consumer call sites. (iteration 4)\n+- Pro-wire workload hypothesis: could not be tested because no runtime query trace exists; retained as a reactivation gate. (iteration 5)\n@@\n - Sunk-cost promotion and one-benchmark promotion: ruled out by conjunctive promotion gates. (iteration 4)\n+- Lazy query-time builds, shelf-with-live-switches, and deleting the flat retrieval manifest: ruled out as unsafe or non-remediating. (iteration 5)\n@@\n-Adversarially validate the shelf recommendation and produce complete wiring and deprecation plans with rollback and roadmap consequences.\n+Synthesis complete after the fifth iteration; no further research focus.\n*** Update File: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n@@\n-  \"openQuestions\": [\n-    {\"id\":\"q-plans\",\"text\":\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\",\"status\":\"open\"}\n-  ],\n+  \"openQuestions\": [],\n@@\n-    {\"id\":\"q-criteria\",\"text\":\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":4,\"answer\":\"A weighted current-fit/materiality/operations/integrity/future/reversibility framework favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100; reactivation requires all evidence gates.\"}\n+    {\"id\":\"q-criteria\",\"text\":\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":4,\"answer\":\"A weighted current-fit/materiality/operations/integrity/future/reversibility framework favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100; reactivation requires all evidence gates.\"},\n+    {\"id\":\"q-plans\",\"text\":\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":5,\"answer\":\"Wire only through distribution/build/refresh/shadow/relevance/cutover gates; shelf by removing live DB modes/code and superseding its roadmap while preserving flat-manifest safety and design evidence.\"}\n@@\n-    {\"id\":\"f-reactivation-gates\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Reactivation requires conjunctive evidence gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\",\"015 roadmap specs\"]}\n+    {\"id\":\"f-reactivation-gates\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Reactivation requires conjunctive evidence gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\",\"015 roadmap specs\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-blast-radius\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"Executable DB coupling outside the DB tree is isolated to the adapter, facade, and adapter tests.\",\"sources\":[\"scoped dependency Grep\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-wire-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A safe wire plan begins with distribution, measurement, refresh ownership, and shadow/relevance gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-005.md\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-shelf-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A formal shelf removes live DB modes/code and supersedes the roadmap while retaining the flat manifest and design evidence.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-005.md\"]}\n@@\n-    {\"approach\":\"Promote from sunk cost or one benchmark\",\"reason\":\"Promotion requires all materiality, quality, and operational gates.\",\"iterations\":[4]}\n+    {\"approach\":\"Promote from sunk cost or one benchmark\",\"reason\":\"Promotion requires all materiality, quality, and operational gates.\",\"iterations\":[4]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Leave DB switches live after shelving\",\"reason\":\"That preserves the current dormant ambiguity.\",\"iterations\":[5]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Lazy query-time database build\",\"reason\":\"Integrity-sensitive reads should not trigger corpus mutation.\",\"iterations\":[5]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Delete the flat retrieval manifest\",\"reason\":\"It is the canonical flat-engine freshness and generation guard.\",\"iterations\":[5]}\n@@\n-    \"iterationsCompleted\": 4,\n-    \"openQuestions\": 1,\n-    \"resolvedQuestions\": 4,\n-    \"keyFindings\": 12,\n+    \"iterationsCompleted\": 5,\n+    \"openQuestions\": 0,\n+    \"resolvedQuestions\": 5,\n+    \"keyFindings\": 15,\n@@\n-    \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":14,\"spec\":7,\"tests\":2,\"measurement\":1}\n+    \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":16,\"spec\":7,\"tests\":5,\"measurement\":1}\n@@\n-  \"status\": \"iterating\",\n+  \"status\": \"synthesizing\",\n*** Update File: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n@@\n | 4 | Decision framework and promotion gates | 0.58 | 6 | complete |\n+| 5 | Adversarial validation and both plans | 0.43 | 6 | complete |\n@@\n-- 4/5 answered; 1 remaining.\n-- Answered: consumer contract; readiness; economics; decision criteria.\n+- 5/5 answered; 0 remaining.\n+- All key questions have evidence-backed answers.\n@@\n-- Ratios: 1.00 -> 0.85 -> 0.72 -> 0.58 (descending, still above threshold)\n+- Ratios: 1.00 -> 0.85 -> 0.72 -> 0.58 -> 0.43 (descending)\n - Minimum iteration floor cleared. Stop remains disabled until run 5 by policy.\n+- Stop reason: maxIterationsReached.\n@@\n - Promotion from sunk cost or one benchmark.\n+- Shelf-with-live-switches, lazy query-time build, and deleting the flat retrieval manifest.\n@@\n-Final adversarial validation plus complete wire and shelf execution plans.\n+Synthesis; no further iteration.\n*** Update File: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n@@\n Reactivation requires all of: a representative workload; approved SLO breach or >=30% and >=25 ms p95 improvement; measured full-corpus build/size; owned deterministic refresh/distribution; strict facade/generation/refusal parity; no material human-judged relevance regression; successful shadow and rollback; and demonstrated persistent-only demand or latency need.\n+\n+## Execution Plans\n+\n+The kept path must prove clean-checkout distribution, build and refresh ownership, full-corpus measurements, strict shadow/oracle/relevance parity, and rollback before changing the default. The shelved path removes DB-only runtime code and mode surfaces, routes the facade directly to the flat engine, retains the flat retrieval manifest, marks the 015 roadmap superseded, and verifies all engine plus corpus suites. [SOURCE: iteration-005.md]\n*** Update File: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log\n@@\n {\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:48:21Z\",\"duration_ms\":782000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":4,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":4,\"elapsed_ms\":782000,\"score\":0.58}}\n+{\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:41Z\",\"duration_ms\":982000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":5,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":5,\"elapsed_ms\":982000,\"score\":0.43}}\n*** End Patch"},"output":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-005.md\nA .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md\nA .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-005.jsonl\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log","metadata":{"diff":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-005.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-005.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-005.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,7 @@\n+DEEP-RESEARCH ITERATION 5\n+\n+STATE SUMMARY: Iteration 5 of 5; 4/5 questions answered; ratios 1.00 -> 0.85 -> 0.72 -> 0.58.\n+\n+Focus Area: Adversarial validation and complete plans for both wiring and shelving.\n+Terminal rule: Complete this iteration, then stop with maxIterationsReached and enter synthesis.\n+Route: mode=research; target_agent=deep-research; execution=single_iteration; state_source=externalized_files.\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,57 @@\n+# Iteration 5: Adversarial Validation and Both Execution Plans\n+\n+## Focus\n+\n+Try to overturn the shelf recommendation, map the live-code blast radius, and deliver complete reversible plans for either operator choice.\n+\n+## Findings\n+\n+1. Shelving has a bounded live-code blast radius. In executable `.mjs`, database-mode references outside `_db` occur only in `_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs`, `_engine/style-library.mjs`, and the DB adapter tests. The four corpus modules have no direct DB imports, so their API need not change. [SOURCE: scoped Grep for `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE|styleDatabaseMode|persistent-adapter|_db/...` under `.opencode/**/*.mjs`]\n+2. The flat engine is not an unsafe fallback. Its dedicated suite covers byte-stable non-writing checks, eligibility-first behavior, source-scan fallback, generation/path/hash hydration guards, invalidation, and proof behavior. It rejects poisoned derived fields and stale manifests before query, and enforces generation, rights, byte, and path-escape guards during hydration. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/index.mjs:1-10] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/check-stable.test.mjs:14-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/hydrate-guard.test.mjs:20-163]\n+3. The strongest pro-wire counterargument is repeat-query cost: the legacy engine reconstructs freshness and disposable search repeatedly, while the persistent implementation already has safe publication and richer retrieval. Wiring now would be rational if real design sessions issue enough queries to breach an approved latency SLO and a clean-checkout publication lifecycle is already funded. Neither condition is evidenced, so the counterargument does not overturn the recommendation. [SOURCE: iterations 1-3]\n+4. **Wiring plan if kept:** (a) preserve the facade and flat files as content authority; (b) choose and document clean-checkout distribution, either checked-in immutable generation under a size budget or mandatory install/prewarm build; (c) build and publish a real full-corpus generation, record size/build telemetry, and verify status/rollback; (d) add authoritative refresh ownership after corpus extraction plus periodic reconciliation; (e) run legacy/persistent shadow against representative consumer requests, strict oracle/refusal/generation parity, and human relevance judgments; (f) meet every promotion gate from iteration 4; (g) switch the adapter default to persistent while retaining an explicit legacy kill switch for a bounded observation window; (h) monitor pointer/generation/vector failures and latency; (i) remove dual-mode code only after the window. Rollback is one manifest-pointer reversal plus the legacy kill switch. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-87] [SOURCE: iteration-004.md]\n+5. **Deprecation plan if shelved:** (a) record the decision and mark the 015 roadmap and children superseded/shelved rather than planned; (b) retain 013/015/this research as design evidence and reactivation gates; (c) remove `_db`, DB-only tests/goldens/seeds, `persistent-adapter.mjs`, `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE`, `styleDatabaseMode`, CLI `--backend/--database`, and DB README claims; (d) route `runQuery`/`runHydrate` directly to the existing flat implementation; (e) keep the retrieval manifest because it is the flat engine's generation/freshness contract, then rename/restructure it only in the separate filesystem packet; (f) run the flat engine suite plus all four corpus suites and verify no DB imports/modes/artifacts remain; (g) remove planned DB evolution from active navigation. Rollback is a targeted Git revert; no data migration exists because no real DB was published. [SOURCE: scoped dependency Grep] [SOURCE: scoped retrieval-manifest Grep] [SOURCE: gap-analysis.md:72-105]\n+6. Preserving dormant runtime code is not a safe middle path. It leaves two supported semantics, mode-dependent failures, roadmap obligations, and documentation drift while providing no user-visible default capability. Preserve knowledge, not an unowned live surface. [INFERENCE: iterations 2-5]\n+\n+## Ruled Out\n+\n+- Shelf by deleting `_retrieval-manifest.json`: it belongs to and protects the flat engine.\n+- Shelf while leaving environment/CLI switches live: that is the current dormant state, not remediation.\n+- Wire by lazy query-time build: integrity-sensitive reads should not unexpectedly walk and mutate the corpus.\n+- Wire without a clean-checkout distribution decision: a missing pointer would make default consumers fail.\n+\n+## Dead Ends\n+\n+- No evidence overturns the shelf recommendation. The remaining pro-wire case is explicitly contingent on future measured workload and funded lifecycle ownership.\n+\n+## Edge Cases\n+\n+- Ambiguous input: whether to preserve generic canonicalizer/telemetry/oracle modules. They are currently DB-owned and have no independent consumer; preserve their design in docs/Git, not live source, unless a concrete reuse is identified before removal.\n+- Contradictory evidence: the recently built foundation is high quality, but removing it can still be correct because quality does not create demand.\n+- Missing dependencies: the operator must approve final deletion scope and the proposed numeric reactivation thresholds.\n+- Partial success: plans are implementation-ready at decision level but intentionally do not enumerate every deleted file.\n+\n+## Sources Consulted\n+\n+- Detached state/config/strategy through iteration 4.\n+- Scoped DB-mode/import dependency search.\n+- Scoped retrieval-manifest/build ownership search.\n+- Flat engine test index, stable-check tests, and hydration-guard tests.\n+\n+## Assessment\n+\n+- New information ratio: 0.43\n+- Novelty justification: The bounded blast radius and both sequenced execution plans are new; the final recommendation consolidates prior evidence.\n+- Questions addressed: safe wiring and deprecation plans.\n+- Questions answered: both paths are reversible; shelving is lower-risk and better supported now.\n+- Confidence: high on recommendation and blast radius; medium on exact implementation scope pending a dedicated plan/review.\n+\n+## Reflection\n+\n+- What worked and why: dependency search confirmed that storage choice is isolated enough for a clean shelf without consumer rewrites.\n+- What did not work and why: no runtime trace exists to test the strongest pro-wire hypothesis; it remains a reactivation gate.\n+- What I would do differently: if the operator chooses wire despite the recommendation, make the first implementation task measurement and distribution proof, not default flipping.\n+\n+## Recommended Next Focus\n+\n+Synthesize the five iterations into the final decision report. Stop reason: `maxIterationsReached`.\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-005.jsonl\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-005.jsonl\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-005.jsonl\n@@ -0,0 +1,4 @@\n+{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":5,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":5,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Adversarial validation and complete wire/shelf execution plans\",\"findingsCount\":6,\"newInfoRatio\":0.43,\"noveltyJustification\":\"The bounded blast radius and both sequenced execution plans are new; the final recommendation consolidates prior evidence.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Delete the flat retrieval manifest when shelving\",\"Leave database environment and CLI switches live after shelving\",\"Build the database lazily on query\",\"Wire without clean-checkout distribution ownership\",\"Keep dormant runtime as a compromise\"],\"focusTrack\":\"execution\",\"edgeCase\":\"contradictory-evidence\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"DB mode/import dependency search\",\"retrieval manifest ownership search\",\"engine test index\",\"check-stable.test.mjs\",\"hydrate-guard.test.mjs\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:40Z\",\"durationMs\":198000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-blast-radius\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"Executable DB coupling outside the DB tree is isolated to the adapter, facade, and adapter tests.\"}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-wire-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A safe wire plan begins with distribution, full-corpus measurement, refresh ownership, shadow/relevance gates, then bounded cutover.\"}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-shelf-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A formal shelf removes live DB modes/code and supersedes the roadmap while retaining the flat retrieval manifest and design evidence.\"}\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\n@@ -9,4 +9,7 @@\n {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"min_iterations_guard_pass\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":4,\"iterationCount\":3,\"minIterations\":3,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:01Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":3,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:01Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n {\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":4,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":4,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Weighted decision framework and reversible promotion gates\",\"findingsCount\":6,\"newInfoRatio\":0.58,\"noveltyJustification\":\"The scoring model, formal shelf definition, and conjunctive promotion gates are new; underlying evidence is synthesized from prior iterations.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Retain dormant code indefinitely for optionality\",\"Promote because implementation cost was recently incurred\",\"Promote on one performance benchmark\",\"Keep undocumented shadow and persistent modes as a compromise\"],\"focusTrack\":\"decision\",\"edgeCase\":\"ambiguous-input\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"consumer feature-token search\",\"002-js-capabilities/spec.md\",\"003-measured-native/spec.md\",\"004-growth/spec.md\",\"gap-analysis.md\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:48:20Z\",\"durationMs\":196000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":4,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:48:21Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n+{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":5,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":5,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Adversarial validation and complete wire/shelf execution plans\",\"findingsCount\":6,\"newInfoRatio\":0.43,\"noveltyJustification\":\"The bounded blast radius and both sequenced execution plans are new; the final recommendation consolidates prior evidence.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Delete the flat retrieval manifest when shelving\",\"Leave database environment and CLI switches live after shelving\",\"Build the database lazily on query\",\"Wire without clean-checkout distribution ownership\",\"Keep dormant runtime as a compromise\"],\"focusTrack\":\"execution\",\"edgeCase\":\"contradictory-evidence\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"DB mode/import dependency search\",\"retrieval manifest ownership search\",\"engine test index\",\"check-stable.test.mjs\",\"hydrate-guard.test.mjs\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:40Z\",\"durationMs\":198000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n+{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":5,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:41Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n+{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"max_iterations_reached\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":5,\"stopReason\":\"maxIterationsReached\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:41Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n@@ -23,9 +23,9 @@\n - [x] What contract and workload do design-interface, design-motion, design-audit, and design-foundations actually require from the styles library?\n - [x] How complete is the persistent implementation, and what exact work remains to make it the default and populate a real database?\n - [x] What measurable benefits justify SQLite at the present corpus size, and what recurring operational costs would default persistence introduce?\n - [x] Which decision criteria and thresholds should govern keep versus shelve?\n-- [ ] What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans, including rollback and preservation of useful evidence assets?\n+- [x] What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans, including rollback and preservation of useful evidence assets?\n <!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n ## 5. Answered Questions\n@@ -33,8 +33,9 @@\n - The four consumers require a bounded, generation-safe `runQuery`/`runHydrate` facade and degrade safely when retrieval is unavailable; none requires SQLite specifically. (iteration 1)\n - The persistent implementation is mature, but a real default requires a published initial generation plus explicit build/distribution/refresh/repair ownership and live cutover evidence. (iteration 2)\n - Persistent selection avoids substantial repeat-query corpus I/O, but the only direct speed assertion is a 20-style fixture; present-scale materiality, workload demand, relevance quality, and lifecycle cost remain unmeasured. (iteration 3)\n - A weighted present-state framework scores formal shelving 85/100 versus wiring 54/100; reversal requires conjunctive workload, materiality, lifecycle, parity, relevance, shadow, rollback, and demand gates. (iteration 4)\n+- Both paths are reversible: wiring requires distribution, build/refresh ownership, shadow/relevance gates, then cutover; shelving removes live DB code/modes and supersedes the roadmap while preserving the flat manifest and design evidence. (iteration 5)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n \n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n <!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n@@ -43,8 +44,9 @@\n - Consumer-to-facade tracing: showed that backend choice is isolated below all four corpus modules. (iteration 1)\n - Implementation-versus-integration separation: distinguished mature database code from the absent operational lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n - Evidence-class separation: distinguished correctness, directional speed, material speed, and product demand. (iteration 3)\n - Weighted scoring and sensitivity check: made judgment explicit and showed the result is not dependent on one criterion. (iteration 4)\n+- Dependency and manifest-ownership scans: bounded the shelf blast radius and protected the flat engine's retrieval manifest. (iteration 5)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n ## 7. What Failed\n@@ -52,8 +54,9 @@\n - Initial wildcard include search: returned no files because the path/include shape was too broad; replaced with an exact call-site search. (iteration 1)\n - First-segment indexer read: did not reach the build function, so operator and README evidence were used to triangulate the published lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n - Exact ROI modeling: blocked by the absent full-corpus database, workload trace, build timing, and human relevance set. (iteration 3)\n - Broad feature-token search: included database internals, so its absence claim was narrowed to consumer call sites. (iteration 4)\n+- Pro-wire workload hypothesis: could not be tested because no runtime query trace exists; retained as a reactivation gate. (iteration 5)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n ## 8. Exhausted Approaches\n@@ -65,8 +68,9 @@\n - Synthetic 20-style timing as production justification: ruled out because it proves direction but records no materiality. (iteration 3)\n - Correctness suite as demand proof: ruled out because safety and usefulness are separate questions. (iteration 3)\n - Dormant-code optionality: ruled out because Git history and decision evidence preserve recovery without active runtime ownership. (iteration 4)\n - Sunk-cost promotion and one-benchmark promotion: ruled out by conjunctive promotion gates. (iteration 4)\n+- Lazy query-time builds, shelf-with-live-switches, and deleting the flat retrieval manifest: ruled out as unsafe or non-remediating. (iteration 5)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n ## 9. Ruled-Out Directions\n@@ -82,9 +86,9 @@\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n ## 11. Next Focus\n \n-Adversarially validate the shelf recommendation and produce complete wiring and deprecation plans with rollback and roadmap consequences.\n+Synthesis complete after the fifth iteration; no further research focus.\n <!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n \n ## 12. Known Context\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n@@ -1,13 +1,12 @@\n {\n-  \"openQuestions\": [\n-    {\"id\":\"q-plans\",\"text\":\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\",\"status\":\"open\"}\n-  ],\n+  \"openQuestions\": [],\n   \"resolvedQuestions\": [\n     {\"id\":\"q-consumers\",\"text\":\"What contract and workload do the four design-mode corpus consumers require?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":1,\"answer\":\"A bounded generation-safe query/hydration facade; no consumer requires SQLite specifically.\"},\n     {\"id\":\"q-readiness\",\"text\":\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":2,\"answer\":\"Technically mature, but missing a published artifact and an owned build/distribution/refresh/repair lifecycle plus live cutover evidence.\"},\n     {\"id\":\"q-economics\",\"text\":\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":3,\"answer\":\"It credibly removes repeat-query corpus I/O, but current-scale materiality and demand are unmeasured while defaulting introduces permanent publication, freshness, migration, monitoring, and repair ownership.\"},\n-    {\"id\":\"q-criteria\",\"text\":\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":4,\"answer\":\"A weighted current-fit/materiality/operations/integrity/future/reversibility framework favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100; reactivation requires all evidence gates.\"}\n+    {\"id\":\"q-criteria\",\"text\":\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":4,\"answer\":\"A weighted current-fit/materiality/operations/integrity/future/reversibility framework favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100; reactivation requires all evidence gates.\"},\n+    {\"id\":\"q-plans\",\"text\":\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":5,\"answer\":\"Wire only through distribution/build/refresh/shadow/relevance/cutover gates; shelf by removing live DB modes/code and superseding its roadmap while preserving flat-manifest safety and design evidence.\"}\n   ],\n   \"keyFindings\": [\n     {\"id\":\"f-consumer-facade\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"All four corpus modules use the storage-neutral runQuery/runHydrate facade.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:181-207\",\"four corpus modules\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-content-authority\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Flat artifacts remain authoritative content under persistent selection.\",\"sources\":[\"consumer hydration calls\"]},\n@@ -19,9 +18,12 @@\n     {\"id\":\"f-evidence-gap\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"No published generation, active profile, workload trace, full-corpus timing, or human relevance set exists.\",\"sources\":[\"013 research.md:38-44\",\"foundation implementation-summary.md:117-123\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-default-not-cleared\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Present evidence does not clear a threshold for permanent default-path ownership.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-003.md\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-score-shelf\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Weighted present-state score favors shelving 85/100 over wiring 54/100.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-formal-shelf\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Formal shelving removes the supported runtime surface rather than preserving undocumented dormant modes.\",\"sources\":[\"gap-analysis.md:168-171\",\"iteration-004.md\"]},\n-    {\"id\":\"f-reactivation-gates\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Reactivation requires conjunctive evidence gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\",\"015 roadmap specs\"]}\n+    {\"id\":\"f-reactivation-gates\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Reactivation requires conjunctive evidence gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\",\"015 roadmap specs\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-blast-radius\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"Executable DB coupling outside the DB tree is isolated to the adapter, facade, and adapter tests.\",\"sources\":[\"scoped dependency Grep\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-wire-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A safe wire plan begins with distribution, measurement, refresh ownership, and shadow/relevance gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-005.md\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-shelf-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A formal shelf removes live DB modes/code and supersedes the roadmap while retaining the flat manifest and design evidence.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-005.md\"]}\n   ],\n   \"ruledOutDirections\": [\n     {\"approach\":\"Rewrite consumers for a database API\",\"reason\":\"The existing facade already isolates backend selection.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Move authoritative content into SQLite\",\"reason\":\"Consumer hydration semantics rely on bounded flat artifacts.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n@@ -29,18 +31,21 @@\n     {\"approach\":\"Use feature richness as proof of value\",\"reason\":\"Implemented supply does not establish observed consumer demand.\",\"iterations\":[2]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Promote based on the 20-style timing assertion\",\"reason\":\"It proves directionality but records no current-scale materiality.\",\"iterations\":[3]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Treat correctness coverage as product demand\",\"reason\":\"Safety evidence does not establish workload value.\",\"iterations\":[3]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Keep dormant modes indefinitely for optionality\",\"reason\":\"Git history preserves recovery without active maintenance ownership.\",\"iterations\":[4]},\n-    {\"approach\":\"Promote from sunk cost or one benchmark\",\"reason\":\"Promotion requires all materiality, quality, and operational gates.\",\"iterations\":[4]}\n+    {\"approach\":\"Promote from sunk cost or one benchmark\",\"reason\":\"Promotion requires all materiality, quality, and operational gates.\",\"iterations\":[4]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Leave DB switches live after shelving\",\"reason\":\"That preserves the current dormant ambiguity.\",\"iterations\":[5]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Lazy query-time database build\",\"reason\":\"Integrity-sensitive reads should not trigger corpus mutation.\",\"iterations\":[5]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Delete the flat retrieval manifest\",\"reason\":\"It is the canonical flat-engine freshness and generation guard.\",\"iterations\":[5]}\n   ],\n   \"metrics\": {\n-    \"iterationsCompleted\": 4,\n-    \"openQuestions\": 1,\n-    \"resolvedQuestions\": 4,\n-    \"keyFindings\": 12,\n+    \"iterationsCompleted\": 5,\n+    \"openQuestions\": 0,\n+    \"resolvedQuestions\": 5,\n+    \"keyFindings\": 15,\n     \"convergenceScore\": 0.0,\n-    \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":14,\"spec\":7,\"tests\":2,\"measurement\":1}\n+    \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":16,\"spec\":7,\"tests\":5,\"measurement\":1}\n   },\n-  \"status\": \"iterating\",\n+  \"status\": \"synthesizing\",\n   \"sessionId\": \"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\n   \"generation\": 1\n }\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n@@ -7,18 +7,20 @@\n | 1 | Consumer contract and runtime path | 1.00 | 5 | complete |\n | 2 | Persistent readiness and missing wiring | 0.85 | 6 | complete |\n | 3 | Current-scale economics and evidence | 0.72 | 7 | complete |\n | 4 | Decision framework and promotion gates | 0.58 | 6 | complete |\n+| 5 | Adversarial validation and both plans | 0.43 | 6 | complete |\n \n ## Question Status\n \n-- 4/5 answered; 1 remaining.\n-- Answered: consumer contract; readiness; economics; decision criteria.\n+- 5/5 answered; 0 remaining.\n+- All key questions have evidence-backed answers.\n \n ## Convergence Trend\n \n-- Ratios: 1.00 -> 0.85 -> 0.72 -> 0.58 (descending, still above threshold)\n+- Ratios: 1.00 -> 0.85 -> 0.72 -> 0.58 -> 0.43 (descending)\n - Minimum iteration floor cleared. Stop remains disabled until run 5 by policy.\n+- Stop reason: maxIterationsReached.\n - Stop policy: max-iterations; convergence is telemetry until run 5.\n \n ## Dead Ends\n \n@@ -29,8 +31,9 @@\n - Synthetic fixture speed as a production business case.\n - Correctness tests as proof of demand.\n - Dormant runtime as harmless optionality.\n - Promotion from sunk cost or one benchmark.\n+- Shelf-with-live-switches, lazy query-time build, and deleting the flat retrieval manifest.\n \n ## Next Focus\n \n-Final adversarial validation plus complete wire and shelf execution plans.\n+Synthesis; no further iteration.\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n@@ -31,4 +31,8 @@\n \n Weighted present-state scoring favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100 across current consumer fit, measured material value, operational ownership, integrity/rollback, future leverage, and reversibility. The database wins integrity and future leverage; shelving wins the higher-weight present-use and ownership criteria. [SOURCE: iteration-004.md]\n \n Reactivation requires all of: a representative workload; approved SLO breach or >=30% and >=25 ms p95 improvement; measured full-corpus build/size; owned deterministic refresh/distribution; strict facade/generation/refusal parity; no material human-judged relevance regression; successful shadow and rollback; and demonstrated persistent-only demand or latency need.\n+\n+## Execution Plans\n+\n+The kept path must prove clean-checkout distribution, build and refresh ownership, full-corpus measurements, strict shadow/oracle/relevance parity, and rollback before changing the default. The shelved path removes DB-only runtime code and mode surfaces, routes the facade directly to the flat engine, retains the flat retrieval manifest, marks the 015 roadmap superseded, and verifies all engine plus corpus suites. [SOURCE: iteration-005.md]\n\nIndex: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log\n@@ -2,4 +2,5 @@\n {\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:38:01Z\",\"duration_ms\":162000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":1,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":1,\"elapsed_ms\":162000,\"score\":1.0}}\n {\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:41:31Z\",\"duration_ms\":372000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":2,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":2,\"elapsed_ms\":372000,\"score\":0.85}}\n {\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:01Z\",\"duration_ms\":582000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":3,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":3,\"elapsed_ms\":582000,\"score\":0.72}}\n {\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:48:21Z\",\"duration_ms\":782000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":4,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":4,\"elapsed_ms\":782000,\"score\":0.58}}\n+{\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:41Z\",\"duration_ms\":982000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":5,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":5,\"elapsed_ms\":982000,\"score\":0.43}}\n\n","files":[{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-005.md","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-005.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-005.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-005.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-005.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,7 @@\n+DEEP-RESEARCH ITERATION 5\n+\n+STATE SUMMARY: Iteration 5 of 5; 4/5 questions answered; ratios 1.00 -> 0.85 -> 0.72 -> 0.58.\n+\n+Focus Area: Adversarial validation and complete plans for both wiring and shelving.\n+Terminal rule: Complete this iteration, then stop with maxIterationsReached and enter synthesis.\n+Route: mode=research; target_agent=deep-research; execution=single_iteration; state_source=externalized_files.\n","additions":7,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md\n@@ -0,0 +1,57 @@\n+# Iteration 5: Adversarial Validation and Both Execution Plans\n+\n+## Focus\n+\n+Try to overturn the shelf recommendation, map the live-code blast radius, and deliver complete reversible plans for either operator choice.\n+\n+## Findings\n+\n+1. Shelving has a bounded live-code blast radius. In executable `.mjs`, database-mode references outside `_db` occur only in `_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs`, `_engine/style-library.mjs`, and the DB adapter tests. The four corpus modules have no direct DB imports, so their API need not change. [SOURCE: scoped Grep for `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE|styleDatabaseMode|persistent-adapter|_db/...` under `.opencode/**/*.mjs`]\n+2. The flat engine is not an unsafe fallback. Its dedicated suite covers byte-stable non-writing checks, eligibility-first behavior, source-scan fallback, generation/path/hash hydration guards, invalidation, and proof behavior. It rejects poisoned derived fields and stale manifests before query, and enforces generation, rights, byte, and path-escape guards during hydration. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/index.mjs:1-10] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/check-stable.test.mjs:14-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/hydrate-guard.test.mjs:20-163]\n+3. The strongest pro-wire counterargument is repeat-query cost: the legacy engine reconstructs freshness and disposable search repeatedly, while the persistent implementation already has safe publication and richer retrieval. Wiring now would be rational if real design sessions issue enough queries to breach an approved latency SLO and a clean-checkout publication lifecycle is already funded. Neither condition is evidenced, so the counterargument does not overturn the recommendation. [SOURCE: iterations 1-3]\n+4. **Wiring plan if kept:** (a) preserve the facade and flat files as content authority; (b) choose and document clean-checkout distribution, either checked-in immutable generation under a size budget or mandatory install/prewarm build; (c) build and publish a real full-corpus generation, record size/build telemetry, and verify status/rollback; (d) add authoritative refresh ownership after corpus extraction plus periodic reconciliation; (e) run legacy/persistent shadow against representative consumer requests, strict oracle/refusal/generation parity, and human relevance judgments; (f) meet every promotion gate from iteration 4; (g) switch the adapter default to persistent while retaining an explicit legacy kill switch for a bounded observation window; (h) monitor pointer/generation/vector failures and latency; (i) remove dual-mode code only after the window. Rollback is one manifest-pointer reversal plus the legacy kill switch. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-87] [SOURCE: iteration-004.md]\n+5. **Deprecation plan if shelved:** (a) record the decision and mark the 015 roadmap and children superseded/shelved rather than planned; (b) retain 013/015/this research as design evidence and reactivation gates; (c) remove `_db`, DB-only tests/goldens/seeds, `persistent-adapter.mjs`, `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE`, `styleDatabaseMode`, CLI `--backend/--database`, and DB README claims; (d) route `runQuery`/`runHydrate` directly to the existing flat implementation; (e) keep the retrieval manifest because it is the flat engine's generation/freshness contract, then rename/restructure it only in the separate filesystem packet; (f) run the flat engine suite plus all four corpus suites and verify no DB imports/modes/artifacts remain; (g) remove planned DB evolution from active navigation. Rollback is a targeted Git revert; no data migration exists because no real DB was published. [SOURCE: scoped dependency Grep] [SOURCE: scoped retrieval-manifest Grep] [SOURCE: gap-analysis.md:72-105]\n+6. Preserving dormant runtime code is not a safe middle path. It leaves two supported semantics, mode-dependent failures, roadmap obligations, and documentation drift while providing no user-visible default capability. Preserve knowledge, not an unowned live surface. [INFERENCE: iterations 2-5]\n+\n+## Ruled Out\n+\n+- Shelf by deleting `_retrieval-manifest.json`: it belongs to and protects the flat engine.\n+- Shelf while leaving environment/CLI switches live: that is the current dormant state, not remediation.\n+- Wire by lazy query-time build: integrity-sensitive reads should not unexpectedly walk and mutate the corpus.\n+- Wire without a clean-checkout distribution decision: a missing pointer would make default consumers fail.\n+\n+## Dead Ends\n+\n+- No evidence overturns the shelf recommendation. The remaining pro-wire case is explicitly contingent on future measured workload and funded lifecycle ownership.\n+\n+## Edge Cases\n+\n+- Ambiguous input: whether to preserve generic canonicalizer/telemetry/oracle modules. They are currently DB-owned and have no independent consumer; preserve their design in docs/Git, not live source, unless a concrete reuse is identified before removal.\n+- Contradictory evidence: the recently built foundation is high quality, but removing it can still be correct because quality does not create demand.\n+- Missing dependencies: the operator must approve final deletion scope and the proposed numeric reactivation thresholds.\n+- Partial success: plans are implementation-ready at decision level but intentionally do not enumerate every deleted file.\n+\n+## Sources Consulted\n+\n+- Detached state/config/strategy through iteration 4.\n+- Scoped DB-mode/import dependency search.\n+- Scoped retrieval-manifest/build ownership search.\n+- Flat engine test index, stable-check tests, and hydration-guard tests.\n+\n+## Assessment\n+\n+- New information ratio: 0.43\n+- Novelty justification: The bounded blast radius and both sequenced execution plans are new; the final recommendation consolidates prior evidence.\n+- Questions addressed: safe wiring and deprecation plans.\n+- Questions answered: both paths are reversible; shelving is lower-risk and better supported now.\n+- Confidence: high on recommendation and blast radius; medium on exact implementation scope pending a dedicated plan/review.\n+\n+## Reflection\n+\n+- What worked and why: dependency search confirmed that storage choice is isolated enough for a clean shelf without consumer rewrites.\n+- What did not work and why: no runtime trace exists to test the strongest pro-wire hypothesis; it remains a reactivation gate.\n+- What I would do differently: if the operator chooses wire despite the recommendation, make the first implementation task measurement and distribution proof, not default flipping.\n+\n+## Recommended Next Focus\n+\n+Synthesize the five iterations into the final decision report. Stop reason: `maxIterationsReached`.\n","additions":57,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-005.jsonl","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-005.jsonl","type":"add","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-005.jsonl\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-005.jsonl\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-005.jsonl\n@@ -0,0 +1,4 @@\n+{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":5,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":5,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Adversarial validation and complete wire/shelf execution plans\",\"findingsCount\":6,\"newInfoRatio\":0.43,\"noveltyJustification\":\"The bounded blast radius and both sequenced execution plans are new; the final recommendation consolidates prior evidence.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Delete the flat retrieval manifest when shelving\",\"Leave database environment and CLI switches live after shelving\",\"Build the database lazily on query\",\"Wire without clean-checkout distribution ownership\",\"Keep dormant runtime as a compromise\"],\"focusTrack\":\"execution\",\"edgeCase\":\"contradictory-evidence\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"DB mode/import dependency search\",\"retrieval manifest ownership search\",\"engine test index\",\"check-stable.test.mjs\",\"hydrate-guard.test.mjs\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:40Z\",\"durationMs\":198000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-blast-radius\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"Executable DB coupling outside the DB tree is isolated to the adapter, facade, and adapter tests.\"}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-wire-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A safe wire plan begins with distribution, full-corpus measurement, refresh ownership, shadow/relevance gates, then bounded cutover.\"}\n+{\"type\":\"finding\",\"id\":\"f-shelf-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A formal shelf removes live DB modes/code and supersedes the roadmap while retaining the flat retrieval manifest and design evidence.\"}\n","additions":4,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-resear