nfoRatio\":0.58,\"noveltyJustification\":\"The scoring model, formal shelf definition, and conjunctive promotion gates are new; underlying evidence is synthesized from prior iterations.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Retain dormant code indefinitely for optionality\",\"Promote because implementation cost was recently incurred\",\"Promote on one performance benchmark\",\"Keep undocumented shadow and persistent modes as a compromise\"],\"focusTrack\":\"decision\",\"edgeCase\":\"ambiguous-input\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"consumer feature-token search\",\"002-js-capabilities/spec.md\",\"003-measured-native/spec.md\",\"004-growth/spec.md\",\"gap-analysis.md\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:48:20Z\",\"durationMs\":196000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n {\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":4,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:48:21Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n+{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":5,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":5,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Adversarial validation and complete wire/shelf execution plans\",\"findingsCount\":6,\"newInfoRatio\":0.43,\"noveltyJustification\":\"The bounded blast radius and both sequenced execution plans are new; the final recommendation consolidates prior evidence.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"Delete the flat retrieval manifest when shelving\",\"Leave database environment and CLI switches live after shelving\",\"Build the database lazily on query\",\"Wire without clean-checkout distribution ownership\",\"Keep dormant runtime as a compromise\"],\"focusTrack\":\"execution\",\"edgeCase\":\"contradictory-evidence\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Grep\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"DB mode/import dependency search\",\"retrieval manifest ownership search\",\"engine test index\",\"check-stable.test.mjs\",\"hydrate-guard.test.mjs\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:40Z\",\"durationMs\":198000,\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"executor\":{\"kind\":\"cli-opencode\",\"model\":\"openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast\"},\"graphEvents\":[]}\n+{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"dashboard_generated\",\"iteration\":5,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:41Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n+{\"type\":\"event\",\"event\":\"max_iterations_reached\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":5,\"stopReason\":\"maxIterationsReached\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:41Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1}\n","additions":3,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md","type":"update","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\n@@ -23,9 +23,9 @@\n - [x] What contract and workload do design-interface, design-motion, design-audit, and design-foundations actually require from the styles library?\n - [x] How complete is the persistent implementation, and what exact work remains to make it the default and populate a real database?\n - [x] What measurable benefits justify SQLite at the present corpus size, and what recurring operational costs would default persistence introduce?\n - [x] Which decision criteria and thresholds should govern keep versus shelve?\n-- [ ] What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans, including rollback and preservation of useful evidence assets?\n+- [x] What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans, including rollback and preservation of useful evidence assets?\n <!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n ## 5. Answered Questions\n@@ -33,8 +33,9 @@\n - The four consumers require a bounded, generation-safe `runQuery`/`runHydrate` facade and degrade safely when retrieval is unavailable; none requires SQLite specifically. (iteration 1)\n - The persistent implementation is mature, but a real default requires a published initial generation plus explicit build/distribution/refresh/repair ownership and live cutover evidence. (iteration 2)\n - Persistent selection avoids substantial repeat-query corpus I/O, but the only direct speed assertion is a 20-style fixture; present-scale materiality, workload demand, relevance quality, and lifecycle cost remain unmeasured. (iteration 3)\n - A weighted present-state framework scores formal shelving 85/100 versus wiring 54/100; reversal requires conjunctive workload, materiality, lifecycle, parity, relevance, shadow, rollback, and demand gates. (iteration 4)\n+- Both paths are reversible: wiring requires distribution, build/refresh ownership, shadow/relevance gates, then cutover; shelving removes live DB code/modes and supersedes the roadmap while preserving the flat manifest and design evidence. (iteration 5)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n \n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n <!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n@@ -43,8 +44,9 @@\n - Consumer-to-facade tracing: showed that backend choice is isolated below all four corpus modules. (iteration 1)\n - Implementation-versus-integration separation: distinguished mature database code from the absent operational lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n - Evidence-class separation: distinguished correctness, directional speed, material speed, and product demand. (iteration 3)\n - Weighted scoring and sensitivity check: made judgment explicit and showed the result is not dependent on one criterion. (iteration 4)\n+- Dependency and manifest-ownership scans: bounded the shelf blast radius and protected the flat engine's retrieval manifest. (iteration 5)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n ## 7. What Failed\n@@ -52,8 +54,9 @@\n - Initial wildcard include search: returned no files because the path/include shape was too broad; replaced with an exact call-site search. (iteration 1)\n - First-segment indexer read: did not reach the build function, so operator and README evidence were used to triangulate the published lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n - Exact ROI modeling: blocked by the absent full-corpus database, workload trace, build timing, and human relevance set. (iteration 3)\n - Broad feature-token search: included database internals, so its absence claim was narrowed to consumer call sites. (iteration 4)\n+- Pro-wire workload hypothesis: could not be tested because no runtime query trace exists; retained as a reactivation gate. (iteration 5)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n ## 8. Exhausted Approaches\n@@ -65,8 +68,9 @@\n - Synthetic 20-style timing as production justification: ruled out because it proves direction but records no materiality. (iteration 3)\n - Correctness suite as demand proof: ruled out because safety and usefulness are separate questions. (iteration 3)\n - Dormant-code optionality: ruled out because Git history and decision evidence preserve recovery without active runtime ownership. (iteration 4)\n - Sunk-cost promotion and one-benchmark promotion: ruled out by conjunctive promotion gates. (iteration 4)\n+- Lazy query-time builds, shelf-with-live-switches, and deleting the flat retrieval manifest: ruled out as unsafe or non-remediating. (iteration 5)\n <!-- /ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n ## 9. Ruled-Out Directions\n@@ -82,9 +86,9 @@\n \n <!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n ## 11. Next Focus\n \n-Adversarially validate the shelf recommendation and produce complete wiring and deprecation plans with rollback and roadmap consequences.\n+Synthesis complete after the fifth iteration; no further research focus.\n <!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n \n ## 12. Known Context\n","additions":6,"deletions":2},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json","type":"update","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\n@@ -1,13 +1,12 @@\n {\n-  \"openQuestions\": [\n-    {\"id\":\"q-plans\",\"text\":\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\",\"status\":\"open\"}\n-  ],\n+  \"openQuestions\": [],\n   \"resolvedQuestions\": [\n     {\"id\":\"q-consumers\",\"text\":\"What contract and workload do the four design-mode corpus consumers require?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":1,\"answer\":\"A bounded generation-safe query/hydration facade; no consumer requires SQLite specifically.\"},\n     {\"id\":\"q-readiness\",\"text\":\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":2,\"answer\":\"Technically mature, but missing a published artifact and an owned build/distribution/refresh/repair lifecycle plus live cutover evidence.\"},\n     {\"id\":\"q-economics\",\"text\":\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":3,\"answer\":\"It credibly removes repeat-query corpus I/O, but current-scale materiality and demand are unmeasured while defaulting introduces permanent publication, freshness, migration, monitoring, and repair ownership.\"},\n-    {\"id\":\"q-criteria\",\"text\":\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":4,\"answer\":\"A weighted current-fit/materiality/operations/integrity/future/reversibility framework favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100; reactivation requires all evidence gates.\"}\n+    {\"id\":\"q-criteria\",\"text\":\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":4,\"answer\":\"A weighted current-fit/materiality/operations/integrity/future/reversibility framework favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100; reactivation requires all evidence gates.\"},\n+    {\"id\":\"q-plans\",\"text\":\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":5,\"answer\":\"Wire only through distribution/build/refresh/shadow/relevance/cutover gates; shelf by removing live DB modes/code and superseding its roadmap while preserving flat-manifest safety and design evidence.\"}\n   ],\n   \"keyFindings\": [\n     {\"id\":\"f-consumer-facade\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"All four corpus modules use the storage-neutral runQuery/runHydrate facade.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:181-207\",\"four corpus modules\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-content-authority\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Flat artifacts remain authoritative content under persistent selection.\",\"sources\":[\"consumer hydration calls\"]},\n@@ -19,9 +18,12 @@\n     {\"id\":\"f-evidence-gap\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"No published generation, active profile, workload trace, full-corpus timing, or human relevance set exists.\",\"sources\":[\"013 research.md:38-44\",\"foundation implementation-summary.md:117-123\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-default-not-cleared\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Present evidence does not clear a threshold for permanent default-path ownership.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-003.md\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-score-shelf\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Weighted present-state score favors shelving 85/100 over wiring 54/100.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\"]},\n     {\"id\":\"f-formal-shelf\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Formal shelving removes the supported runtime surface rather than preserving undocumented dormant modes.\",\"sources\":[\"gap-analysis.md:168-171\",\"iteration-004.md\"]},\n-    {\"id\":\"f-reactivation-gates\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Reactivation requires conjunctive evidence gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\",\"015 roadmap specs\"]}\n+    {\"id\":\"f-reactivation-gates\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Reactivation requires conjunctive evidence gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\",\"015 roadmap specs\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-blast-radius\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"Executable DB coupling outside the DB tree is isolated to the adapter, facade, and adapter tests.\",\"sources\":[\"scoped dependency Grep\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-wire-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A safe wire plan begins with distribution, measurement, refresh ownership, and shadow/relevance gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-005.md\"]},\n+    {\"id\":\"f-shelf-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A formal shelf removes live DB modes/code and supersedes the roadmap while retaining the flat manifest and design evidence.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-005.md\"]}\n   ],\n   \"ruledOutDirections\": [\n     {\"approach\":\"Rewrite consumers for a database API\",\"reason\":\"The existing facade already isolates backend selection.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Move authoritative content into SQLite\",\"reason\":\"Consumer hydration semantics rely on bounded flat artifacts.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n@@ -29,18 +31,21 @@\n     {\"approach\":\"Use feature richness as proof of value\",\"reason\":\"Implemented supply does not establish observed consumer demand.\",\"iterations\":[2]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Promote based on the 20-style timing assertion\",\"reason\":\"It proves directionality but records no current-scale materiality.\",\"iterations\":[3]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Treat correctness coverage as product demand\",\"reason\":\"Safety evidence does not establish workload value.\",\"iterations\":[3]},\n     {\"approach\":\"Keep dormant modes indefinitely for optionality\",\"reason\":\"Git history preserves recovery without active maintenance ownership.\",\"iterations\":[4]},\n-    {\"approach\":\"Promote from sunk cost or one benchmark\",\"reason\":\"Promotion requires all materiality, quality, and operational gates.\",\"iterations\":[4]}\n+    {\"approach\":\"Promote from sunk cost or one benchmark\",\"reason\":\"Promotion requires all materiality, quality, and operational gates.\",\"iterations\":[4]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Leave DB switches live after shelving\",\"reason\":\"That preserves the current dormant ambiguity.\",\"iterations\":[5]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Lazy query-time database build\",\"reason\":\"Integrity-sensitive reads should not trigger corpus mutation.\",\"iterations\":[5]},\n+    {\"approach\":\"Delete the flat retrieval manifest\",\"reason\":\"It is the canonical flat-engine freshness and generation guard.\",\"iterations\":[5]}\n   ],\n   \"metrics\": {\n-    \"iterationsCompleted\": 4,\n-    \"openQuestions\": 1,\n-    \"resolvedQuestions\": 4,\n-    \"keyFindings\": 12,\n+    \"iterationsCompleted\": 5,\n+    \"openQuestions\": 0,\n+    \"resolvedQuestions\": 5,\n+    \"keyFindings\": 15,\n     \"convergenceScore\": 0.0,\n-    \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":14,\"spec\":7,\"tests\":2,\"measurement\":1}\n+    \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":16,\"spec\":7,\"tests\":5,\"measurement\":1}\n   },\n-  \"status\": \"iterating\",\n+  \"status\": \"synthesizing\",\n   \"sessionId\": \"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\n   \"generation\": 1\n }\n","additions":17,"deletions":12},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md","type":"update","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\n@@ -7,18 +7,20 @@\n | 1 | Consumer contract and runtime path | 1.00 | 5 | complete |\n | 2 | Persistent readiness and missing wiring | 0.85 | 6 | complete |\n | 3 | Current-scale economics and evidence | 0.72 | 7 | complete |\n | 4 | Decision framework and promotion gates | 0.58 | 6 | complete |\n+| 5 | Adversarial validation and both plans | 0.43 | 6 | complete |\n \n ## Question Status\n \n-- 4/5 answered; 1 remaining.\n-- Answered: consumer contract; readiness; economics; decision criteria.\n+- 5/5 answered; 0 remaining.\n+- All key questions have evidence-backed answers.\n \n ## Convergence Trend\n \n-- Ratios: 1.00 -> 0.85 -> 0.72 -> 0.58 (descending, still above threshold)\n+- Ratios: 1.00 -> 0.85 -> 0.72 -> 0.58 -> 0.43 (descending)\n - Minimum iteration floor cleared. Stop remains disabled until run 5 by policy.\n+- Stop reason: maxIterationsReached.\n - Stop policy: max-iterations; convergence is telemetry until run 5.\n \n ## Dead Ends\n \n@@ -29,8 +31,9 @@\n - Synthetic fixture speed as a production business case.\n - Correctness tests as proof of demand.\n - Dormant runtime as harmless optionality.\n - Promotion from sunk cost or one benchmark.\n+- Shelf-with-live-switches, lazy query-time build, and deleting the flat retrieval manifest.\n \n ## Next Focus\n \n-Final adversarial validation plus complete wire and shelf execution plans.\n+Synthesis; no further iteration.\n","additions":7,"deletions":4},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md","type":"update","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\n@@ -31,4 +31,8 @@\n \n Weighted present-state scoring favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100 across current consumer fit, measured material value, operational ownership, integrity/rollback, future leverage, and reversibility. The database wins integrity and future leverage; shelving wins the higher-weight present-use and ownership criteria. [SOURCE: iteration-004.md]\n \n Reactivation requires all of: a representative workload; approved SLO breach or >=30% and >=25 ms p95 improvement; measured full-corpus build/size; owned deterministic refresh/distribution; strict facade/generation/refusal parity; no material human-judged relevance regression; successful shadow and rollback; and demonstrated persistent-only demand or latency need.\n+\n+## Execution Plans\n+\n+The kept path must prove clean-checkout distribution, build and refresh ownership, full-corpus measurements, strict shadow/oracle/relevance parity, and rollback before changing the default. The shelved path removes DB-only runtime code and mode surfaces, routes the facade directly to the flat engine, retains the flat retrieval manifest, marks the 015 roadmap superseded, and verifies all engine plus corpus suites. [SOURCE: iteration-005.md]\n","additions":4,"deletions":0},{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log","relativePath":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log","type":"update","patch":"Index: /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log\n===================================================================\n--- /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log\n+++ /Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log\n@@ -2,4 +2,5 @@\n {\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:38:01Z\",\"duration_ms\":162000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":1,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":1,\"elapsed_ms\":162000,\"score\":1.0}}\n {\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:41:31Z\",\"duration_ms\":372000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":2,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":2,\"elapsed_ms\":372000,\"score\":0.85}}\n {\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:45:01Z\",\"duration_ms\":582000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":3,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":3,\"elapsed_ms\":582000,\"score\":0.72}}\n {\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:48:21Z\",\"duration_ms\":782000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":4,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":4,\"elapsed_ms\":782000,\"score\":0.58}}\n+{\"event\":\"progress\",\"label\":\"sol-high-fast\",\"at\":\"2026-07-21T08:51:41Z\",\"duration_ms\":982000,\"loop_type\":\"research\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\"generation\":1,\"run\":5,\"status\":\"complete\",\"gauges\":{\"iterations\":5,\"elapsed_ms\":982000,\"score\":0.43}}\n","additions":1,"deletions":0}],"diagnostics":{},"truncated":false},"title":"Success. Updated the following files:\nA .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/prompts/iteration-005.md\nA .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md\nA .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deltas/iter-005.jsonl\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-state.jsonl\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-dashboard.md\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md\nM .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/orchestration-status.log","time":{"start":1784623640376,"end":1784623640409}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07be4e34cb1034de016a5f31c0d000819181ae94ae73828be4"}},"id":"prt_f83da594b001vQLTjvru0SCYNj","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","messageID":"msg_f83da3c73001aBOUrUtcHYsHi2"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1784623641148,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"id":"prt_f83dbb235001Bgc5pVii9Uo3bw","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"8c33c14cc336f3c79d3e0d75ca22f2a2b7481159","messageID":"msg_f83da3c73001aBOUrUtcHYsHi2","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":279759,"input":12078,"output":4872,"reasoning":153,"cache":{"write":0,"read":262656}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1784623644779,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"id":"prt_f83dbc064001UekQYqtO1Ied4L","messageID":"msg_f83dbb4c8001mzy7FKcjG5lS24","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","snapshot":"8c33c14cc336f3c79d3e0d75ca22f2a2b7481159","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1784623663106,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"id":"prt_f83dbcd27001LBcz4Mf7pX5eTu","messageID":"msg_f83dbb4c8001mzy7FKcjG5lS24","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","type":"text","text":"All five forced iterations reached the cap with every key question answered. Final synthesis is consolidating the evidence, decision matrix, both implementation paths, negative knowledge, and convergence report before mechanical artifact verification and lock release.","time":{"start":1784623648039,"end":1784623663104},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_0214130f072a5df6016a5f321ffd888191a874f74f6b38bc25","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784623663252,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_jJ5xCBTQVSIf009FRB2kPkDb","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-001.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-001.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 1: Actual Consumer Contract and Runtime Path\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: \n5: Determine what the four design-mode corpus modules ask from the styles library and whether their contract inherently requires SQLite.\n6: \n7: ## Findings\n8: \n9: 1. All four consumers call the same storage-neutral `runQuery` and `runHydrate` facade. That facade delegates through `persistent-adapter.mjs`, so the consumer API already isolates backend choice; a keep or shelf decision need not change corpus-module call sites. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:181-207]\n10: 2. Every mode forces `usage: 'reference'`, `exactReuse: false`, and a bounded `limit`; the workloads are selection-oriented, not open-ended analytics or bulk traversal. Interface, motion, and foundations ultimately select specifically identified cards, while audit builds only zero to two comparisons. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs:593-632] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/corpus/motion-evidence.mjs:752-822] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs:468-515] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs:818-867]\n11: 3. Generation identity is a hard semantic contract: every consumer rejects or degrades when `query.generationHash` differs from the context plan, and hydration repeats that generation hash. This favors preserving deterministic generation semantics, but not a specific storage technology. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs:622-647] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/corpus/motion-evidence.mjs:808-822] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs:503-515] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs:854-875]\n12: 4. Hydration remains flat-file based even after database selection: consumers request bounded `DESIGN.md`, `source.md`, and sometimes `design-tokens.json` content by ID and generation. SQLite is therefore an index/select layer, not the authoritative content store. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs:566-575] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs:448-457] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs:798-807]\n13: 5. The current legacy query pays a freshness cost on every call: it loads the committed manifest, rebuilds a live manifest from the corpus, byte-compares both, then performs eligibility/ranking/card assembly. SQLite could remove repeated corpus-walk work from normal reads, but only if its generation is built and published reliably. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:123-159]\n14: \n15: ## Ruled Out\n16: \n17: - Treating the consumers as database-specific: their imported contract is the storage-neutral style-library facade.\n18: - Treating SQLite as the content source: hydration still reads authoritative artifacts from the corpus.\n19: \n20: ## Dead Ends\n21: \n22: - Rewriting the four design-mode modules as part of either option is unnecessary unless the response DTO changes, which the current adapter is designed to prevent.\n23: \n24: ## Edge Cases\n25: \n26: - Ambiguous input: \"single source\" could mean metadata/index truth or content truth. This iteration distinguishes them: flat files remain content authority under both options.\n27: - Contradictory evidence: none.\n28: - Missing dependencies: none.\n29: - Partial success: none.\n30: \n31: ## Sources Consulted\n32: \n33: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:73-207`\n34: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs:535-659`\n35: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/corpus/motion-evidence.mjs:700-834`\n36: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs:420-539`\n37: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs:770-899`\n38: \n39: ## Assessment\n40: \n41: - New information ratio: 1.00\n42: - Novelty justification: First iteration established five new contract-level findings from the actual consumers.\n43: - Questions addressed: consumer contract and workload.\n44: - Questions answered: the consumers need a bounded, generation-safe query/hydration facade, not SQLite specifically.\n45: - Confidence: high for static runtime behavior; call frequency in real design sessions is not instrumented here.\n46: \n47: ## Reflection\n48: \n49: - What worked and why: tracing all consumers to the shared facade exposed stable invariants without assuming storage needs.\n50: - What did not work and why: repository-wide wildcard Grep did not accept the initial include shape; a narrower exact call-site search resolved it.\n51: - What I would do differently: inspect adapter and database internals next, preserving the facade as the fixed boundary.\n52: \n53: ## Recommended Next Focus\n54: \n55: Assess persistent-backend completeness: database opening, indexing/build, query parity, hydration behavior, publish/rollback, and the exact missing default-path wiring.\n\n(End of file - total 55 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 1: Actual Consumer Contract and Runtime Path\n\n## Focus\n\nDetermine what the four design-mode corpus modules ask from the styles library and whether their contract inherently requires SQLite.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. All four consumers call the same storage-neutral `runQuery` and `runHydrate` facade. That facade delegates through `persistent-adapter.mjs`, so the consumer API already isolates backend choice; a keep or shelf decision need not change corpus-module call sites. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:181-207]\n2. Every mode forces `usage: 'reference'`, `exactReuse: false`, and a bounded `limit`; the workloads are selection-oriented, not open-ended analytics or bulk traversal. Interface, motion, and foundations ultimately select specifically identified cards, while audit builds only zero to two comparisons. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs:593-632] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/corpus/motion-evidence.mjs:752-822] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs:468-515] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs:818-867]\n3. Generation identity is a hard semantic contract: every consumer rejects or degrades when `query.generationHash` differs from the context plan, and hydration repeats that generation hash. This favors preserving deterministic generation semantics, but not a specific storage technology. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs:622-647] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/corpus/motion-evidence.mjs:808-822] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs:503-515] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs:854-875]\n4. Hydration remains flat-file based even after database selection: consumers request bounded `DESIGN.md`, `source.md`, and sometimes `design-tokens.json` content by ID and generation. SQLite is therefore an index/select layer, not the authoritative content store. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs:566-575] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs:448-457] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs:798-807]\n5. The current legacy query pays a freshness cost on every call: it loads the committed manifest, rebuilds a live manifest from the corpus, byte-compares both, then performs eligibility/ranking/card assembly. SQLite could remove repeated corpus-walk work from normal reads, but only if its generation is built and published reliably. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:123-159]\n\n## Ruled Out\n\n- Treating the consumers as database-specific: their imported contract is the storage-neutral style-library facade.\n- Treating SQLite as the content source: hydration still reads authoritative artifacts from the corpus.\n\n## Dead Ends","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-001.md","text":"# Iteration 1: Actual Consumer Contract and Runtime Path\n\n## Focus\n\nDetermine what the four design-mode corpus modules ask from the styles library and whether their contract inherently requires SQLite.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. All four consumers call the same storage-neutral `runQuery` and `runHydrate` facade. That facade delegates through `persistent-adapter.mjs`, so the consumer API already isolates backend choice; a keep or shelf decision need not change corpus-module call sites. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:181-207]\n2. Every mode forces `usage: 'reference'`, `exactReuse: false`, and a bounded `limit`; the workloads are selection-oriented, not open-ended analytics or bulk traversal. Interface, motion, and foundations ultimately select specifically identified cards, while audit builds only zero to two comparisons. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs:593-632] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/corpus/motion-evidence.mjs:752-822] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs:468-515] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs:818-867]\n3. Generation identity is a hard semantic contract: every consumer rejects or degrades when `query.generationHash` differs from the context plan, and hydration repeats that generation hash. This favors preserving deterministic generation semantics, but not a specific storage technology. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs:622-647] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/corpus/motion-evidence.mjs:808-822] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs:503-515] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs:854-875]\n4. Hydration remains flat-file based even after database selection: consumers request bounded `DESIGN.md`, `source.md`, and sometimes `design-tokens.json` content by ID and generation. SQLite is therefore an index/select layer, not the authoritative content store. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs:566-575] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs:448-457] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs:798-807]\n5. The current legacy query pays a freshness cost on every call: it loads the committed manifest, rebuilds a live manifest from the corpus, byte-compares both, then performs eligibility/ranking/card assembly. SQLite could remove repeated corpus-walk work from normal reads, but only if its generation is built and published reliably. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:123-159]\n\n## Ruled Out\n\n- Treating the consumers as database-specific: their imported contract is the storage-neutral style-library facade.\n- Treating SQLite as the content source: hydration still reads authoritative artifacts from the corpus.\n\n## Dead Ends\n\n- Rewriting the four design-mode modules as part of either option is unnecessary unless the response DTO changes, which the current adapter is designed to prevent.\n\n## Edge Cases\n\n- Ambiguous input: \"single source\" could mean metadata/index truth or content truth. This iteration distinguishes them: flat files remain content authority under both options.\n- Contradictory evidence: none.\n- Missing dependencies: none.\n- Partial success: none.\n\n## Sources Consulted\n\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/style-library.mjs:73-207`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/corpus/relational-exemplar.mjs:535-659`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/corpus/motion-evidence.mjs:700-834`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/corpus/comparison-lane.mjs:420-539`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/corpus/relationship-blueprint.mjs:770-899`\n\n## Assessment\n\n- New information ratio: 1.00\n- Novelty justification: First iteration established five new contract-level findings from the actual consumers.\n- Questions addressed: consumer contract and workload.\n- Questions answered: the consumers need a bounded, generation-safe query/hydration facade, not SQLite specifically.\n- Confidence: high for static runtime behavior; call frequency in real design sessions is not instrumented here.\n\n## Reflection\n\n- What worked and why: tracing all consumers to the shared facade exposed stable invariants without assuming storage needs.\n- What did not work and why: repository-wide wildcard Grep did not accept the initial include shape; a narrower exact call-site search resolved it.\n- What I would do differently: inspect adapter and database internals next, preserving the facade as the fixed boundary.\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\n\nAssess persistent-backend completeness: database opening, indexing/build, query parity, hydration behavior, publish/rollback, and the exact missing default-path wiring.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":55,"totalLines":55,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-001.md","time":{"start":1784623663167,"end":1784623663240}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0214130f072a5df6016a5f322f03688191a425758b3ee68265"}},"id":"prt_f83dc080e0014Dx25GE6qw9cMD","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","messageID":"msg_f83dbb4c8001mzy7FKcjG5lS24"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784623663252,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Q84LVrGvpV5gJqhWmtScDgru","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-003.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-003.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 3: Current-Scale Economics and Evidence Quality\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: \n5: Determine whether the persistent path's present benefits justify its recurring lifecycle and maintenance burden, separating measured evidence from plausible benefit.\n6: \n7: ## Findings\n8: \n9: 1. The legacy path has a real asymptotic and I/O cost: it can rebuild disposable in-memory FTS by reading every eligible `DESIGN.md` (up to 64 KiB each), with fallback scan bounds of 1,290 records or 24 MiB. The styles tree is about 135 MiB locally. Persistent reads avoid this corpus walk. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:18-23] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:81-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:146-184] [SOURCE: command `du -sk .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles`: 138412 KiB]\n10: 2. The only direct adapter speed gate proves merely that persistent is faster on a synthetic 20-style fixture. It records no committed latency, ratio, warm/cold state, or current 1,290-style result. This supports directionality, not materiality. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/__tests__/adapter.test.mjs:107-132]\n11: 3. The strongest correctness evidence is excellent but orthogonal to default-path value: 69 tests cover atomic publication, telemetry, full-matrix oracle replay, and 1x/10x/100x determinism. They prove that the system can be operated safely, not that current callers need its capabilities or that end-to-end latency crosses an SLO. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:50-57] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:101-111]\n12: 4. Product-quality evidence is explicitly incomplete: there is no active published generation or embedding profile in the workspace; broad positive query shapes often admit all 1,290 bundles; relevance labels are authored/silver seed data rather than human gold; and live-corpus stage/SLO evidence remains open. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:38-44] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:117-123]\n13: 5. Current-scale benefit is therefore narrow but credible: lower repeat-query I/O/latency and stable immutable snapshots. Advanced vector, cursor, multimodal, and growth benefits are future options, not present requirements; the roadmap itself gates native/growth work on measured SLO or 10x-100x scale. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/spec.md:40-63] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:77-95]\n14: 6. Keeping SQLite as default creates recurring obligations independent of its small source footprint: generate and publish on corpus changes, distribute or bootstrap generations, retain rollback artifacts, migrate schema, monitor/repair vectors, diagnose pointer/generation failures, and keep dual parity during rollout. Those are operational state surfaces that the flat-file default does not currently own. [INFERENCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-87 and iteration 2]\n15: 7. At observed scale and evidence, the value case has not cleared a default-path threshold. This is not evidence that SQLite is slow or broken; it is negative knowledge that the missing workload, relevance, and lifecycle evidence makes permanent default ownership unjustified now. [INFERENCE: findings 1-6]\n16: \n17: ## Ruled Out\n18: \n19: - Using the 20-style timing test as a production business case.\n20: - Counting the 69-test correctness suite as proof of caller demand.\n21: - Charging the whole 135 MiB corpus as database overhead; the database projection size is unknown because no real generation exists.\n22: \n23: ## Dead Ends\n24: \n25: - Exact cost modeling is impossible without a real build artifact, build telemetry, query frequency, and representative p50/p95 traces.\n26: \n27: ## Edge Cases\n28: \n29: - Ambiguous input: maintenance cost could be low if corpus updates are rare and DB generation is committed; no ownership or cadence evidence confirms that assumption.\n30: - Contradictory evidence: persistent is directionally faster, yet the default-path recommendation can still be \"not now\" because materiality and operations are unproven.\n31: - Missing dependencies: real database size/build time, production query frequency, current-scale latency, and human relevance judgments.\n32: - Partial success: a qualitative economic decision is possible; a numerical ROI is not.\n33: \n34: ## Sources Consulted\n35: \n36: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/__tests__/adapter.test.mjs:1-132`\n37: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:1-238`\n38: - `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:1-126`\n39: - `.opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:1-283`\n40: - `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/spec.md:1-73`\n41: - Local read-only size measurement of the styles, `_db`, and `_engine` trees.\n42: \n43: ## Assessment\n44: \n45: - New information ratio: 0.72\n46: - Novelty justification: Four findings are new economic evidence, two synthesize prior architecture facts, and one is a new negative-knowledge conclusion.\n47: - Questions addressed: measurable benefits and recurring costs.\n48: - Questions answered: repeat-query efficiency is plausible and directionally proven, but materiality and product value are not; default ownership is not justified by current evidence.\n49: - Confidence: high on evidence gaps and legacy I/O shape; medium on operational cost magnitude.\n50: \n51: ## Reflection\n52: \n53: - What worked and why: distinguishing correctness, performance direction, performance materiality, and product demand prevented sunk-cost reasoning.\n54: - What did not work and why: no committed full-corpus DB exists, so exact size/build/query measurements could not be gathered without violating the research-only scope.\n55: - What I would do differently: encode explicit promotion thresholds so a future decision can be evidence-driven rather than permanent.\n56: \n57: ## Recommended Next Focus\n58: \n59: Build a weighted decision framework with present-state scoring and reversible promotion gates, then test whether shelving or wiring best fits those scores.\n\n(End of file - total 59 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 3: Current-Scale Economics and Evidence Quality\n\n## Focus\n\nDetermine whether the persistent path's present benefits justify its recurring lifecycle and maintenance burden, separating measured evidence from plausible benefit.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. The legacy path has a real asymptotic and I/O cost: it can rebuild disposable in-memory FTS by reading every eligible `DESIGN.md` (up to 64 KiB each), with fallback scan bounds of 1,290 records or 24 MiB. The styles tree is about 135 MiB locally. Persistent reads avoid this corpus walk. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:18-23] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:81-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:146-184] [SOURCE: command `du -sk .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles`: 138412 KiB]\n2. The only direct adapter speed gate proves merely that persistent is faster on a synthetic 20-style fixture. It records no committed latency, ratio, warm/cold state, or current 1,290-style result. This supports directionality, not materiality. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/__tests__/adapter.test.mjs:107-132]\n3. The strongest correctness evidence is excellent but orthogonal to default-path value: 69 tests cover atomic publication, telemetry, full-matrix oracle replay, and 1x/10x/100x determinism. They prove that the system can be operated safely, not that current callers need its capabilities or that end-to-end latency crosses an SLO. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:50-57] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:101-111]\n4. Product-quality evidence is explicitly incomplete: there is no active published generation or embedding profile in the workspace; broad positive query shapes often admit all 1,290 bundles; relevance labels are authored/silver seed data rather than human gold; and live-corpus stage/SLO evidence remains open. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:38-44] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:117-123]\n5. Current-scale benefit is therefore narrow but credible: lower repeat-query I/O/latency and stable immutable snapshots. Advanced vector, cursor, multimodal, and growth benefits are future options, not present requirements; the roadmap itself gates native/growth work on measured SLO or 10x-100x scale. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/spec.md:40-63] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:77-95]\n6. Keeping SQLite as default creates recurring obligations independent of its small source footprint: generate and publish on corpus changes, distribute or bootstrap generations, retain rollback artifacts, migrate schema, monitor/repair vectors, diagnose pointer/generation failures, and keep dual parity during rollout. Those are operational state surfaces that the flat-file default does not currently own. [INFERENCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-87 and iteration 2]\n7. At observed scale and evidence, the value case has not cleared a default-path threshold. This is not evidence that SQLite is slow or broken; it is negative knowledge that the missing workload, relevance, and lifecycle evidence makes permanent default ownership unjustified now. [INFERENCE: findings 1-6]\n\n## Ruled Out\n\n- Using the 20-style timing test as a production business case.\n- Counting the 69-test correctness suite as proof of caller demand.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-003.md","text":"# Iteration 3: Current-Scale Economics and Evidence Quality\n\n## Focus\n\nDetermine whether the persistent path's present benefits justify its recurring lifecycle and maintenance burden, separating measured evidence from plausible benefit.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. The legacy path has a real asymptotic and I/O cost: it can rebuild disposable in-memory FTS by reading every eligible `DESIGN.md` (up to 64 KiB each), with fallback scan bounds of 1,290 records or 24 MiB. The styles tree is about 135 MiB locally. Persistent reads avoid this corpus walk. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:18-23] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:81-127] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:146-184] [SOURCE: command `du -sk .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles`: 138412 KiB]\n2. The only direct adapter speed gate proves merely that persistent is faster on a synthetic 20-style fixture. It records no committed latency, ratio, warm/cold state, or current 1,290-style result. This supports directionality, not materiality. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/__tests__/adapter.test.mjs:107-132]\n3. The strongest correctness evidence is excellent but orthogonal to default-path value: 69 tests cover atomic publication, telemetry, full-matrix oracle replay, and 1x/10x/100x determinism. They prove that the system can be operated safely, not that current callers need its capabilities or that end-to-end latency crosses an SLO. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:50-57] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:101-111]\n4. Product-quality evidence is explicitly incomplete: there is no active published generation or embedding profile in the workspace; broad positive query shapes often admit all 1,290 bundles; relevance labels are authored/silver seed data rather than human gold; and live-corpus stage/SLO evidence remains open. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:38-44] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:117-123]\n5. Current-scale benefit is therefore narrow but credible: lower repeat-query I/O/latency and stable immutable snapshots. Advanced vector, cursor, multimodal, and growth benefits are future options, not present requirements; the roadmap itself gates native/growth work on measured SLO or 10x-100x scale. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/spec.md:40-63] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:77-95]\n6. Keeping SQLite as default creates recurring obligations independent of its small source footprint: generate and publish on corpus changes, distribute or bootstrap generations, retain rollback artifacts, migrate schema, monitor/repair vectors, diagnose pointer/generation failures, and keep dual parity during rollout. Those are operational state surfaces that the flat-file default does not currently own. [INFERENCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-87 and iteration 2]\n7. At observed scale and evidence, the value case has not cleared a default-path threshold. This is not evidence that SQLite is slow or broken; it is negative knowledge that the missing workload, relevance, and lifecycle evidence makes permanent default ownership unjustified now. [INFERENCE: findings 1-6]\n\n## Ruled Out\n\n- Using the 20-style timing test as a production business case.\n- Counting the 69-test correctness suite as proof of caller demand.\n- Charging the whole 135 MiB corpus as database overhead; the database projection size is unknown because no real generation exists.\n\n## Dead Ends\n\n- Exact cost modeling is impossible without a real build artifact, build telemetry, query frequency, and representative p50/p95 traces.\n\n## Edge Cases\n\n- Ambiguous input: maintenance cost could be low if corpus updates are rare and DB generation is committed; no ownership or cadence evidence confirms that assumption.\n- Contradictory evidence: persistent is directionally faster, yet the default-path recommendation can still be \"not now\" because materiality and operations are unproven.\n- Missing dependencies: real database size/build time, production query frequency, current-scale latency, and human relevance judgments.\n- Partial success: a qualitative economic decision is possible; a numerical ROI is not.\n\n## Sources Consulted\n\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/__tests__/adapter.test.mjs:1-132`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/rank-fts.mjs:1-238`\n- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:1-126`\n- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/013-styles-database-rust-opportunities/research/lineages/sol-opencode/research.md:1-283`\n- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/spec.md:1-73`\n- Local read-only size measurement of the styles, `_db`, and `_engine` trees.\n\n## Assessment\n\n- New information ratio: 0.72\n- Novelty justification: Four findings are new economic evidence, two synthesize prior architecture facts, and one is a new negative-knowledge conclusion.\n- Questions addressed: measurable benefits and recurring costs.\n- Questions answered: repeat-query efficiency is plausible and directionally proven, but materiality and product value are not; default ownership is not justified by current evidence.\n- Confidence: high on evidence gaps and legacy I/O shape; medium on operational cost magnitude.\n\n## Reflection\n\n- What worked and why: distinguishing correctness, performance direction, performance materiality, and product demand prevented sunk-cost reasoning.\n- What did not work and why: no committed full-corpus DB exists, so exact size/build/query measurements could not be gathered without violating the research-only scope.\n- What I would do differently: encode explicit promotion thresholds so a future decision can be evidence-driven rather than permanent.\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\n\nBuild a weighted decision framework with present-state scoring and reversible promotion gates, then test whether shelving or wiring best fits those scores.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":59,"totalLines":59,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-003.md","time":{"start":1784623663192,"end":1784623663248}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0214130f072a5df6016a5f322f03a08191930a3e8614731d04"}},"id":"prt_f83dc0852001sx8w8vPdpc32Z3","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","messageID":"msg_f83dbb4c8001mzy7FKcjG5lS24"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784623663266,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_hziXzfQgwLHs9ExcVVYBsI78","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-002.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-002.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 2: Persistent Backend Readiness and Missing Wiring\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: \n5: Assess whether the database is merely a sketch or a deployable projection, then enumerate what still separates it from a safe default.\n6: \n7: ## Findings\n8: \n9: 1. The persistent implementation is technically substantial, not a stub: schema v2 contains normalized style/provenance/artifact/facet/section tables, external-content FTS5, embeddings/jobs/vectors, relationships, immutable corpus generations, and indexes. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/schema.mjs:35-269]\n10: 2. Publication and rollback are implemented around immutable generation files plus an atomic `.current.json` manifest pointer. The operator supports `status`, `build`, `cutover`, `rollback`, and vector `repair`, retaining current plus one rollback generation. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:6-49] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/operator.mjs:75-185] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/operator.mjs:207-247]\n11: 3. Query semantics exceed today's consumer needs: structured, FTS5, and optional vector lanes feed deterministic weighted RRF, generation-bound cursors, attribution, and channel-local degradation. Consumers currently ask for at most five reference cards and do not supply evidence that vector search or pagination is required. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:13-25] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:168-294] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:364-510] [INFERENCE: iteration 1 consumer evidence]\n12: 4. The code deliberately avoids implicit construction: `buildStyleDatabase()` is never invoked by query or hydrate, and the operator requires an explicit corpus path. Therefore changing the mode default alone would fail on a clean checkout because neither the default SQLite artifact nor its pointer exists. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:40-43] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/operator.mjs:213-226] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/schema.mjs:11-23]\n13: 5. A production cutover needs more than one successful build: it needs a refresh owner tied to corpus extraction/update, artifact distribution or deterministic local bootstrap, status/repair observability, and a failure policy. No such default-path lifecycle is visible in the facade or operator; reads fail closed rather than auto-building, which is correct for integrity but leaves operations unowned. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-49] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs:144-166]\n14: 6. Shadow mode is a useful migration gate but its parity comparison intentionally tolerates generation hashes, content hashes, score values, and ranking mode. It checks projected cards and eligibility, not strict rank/score equivalence; default cutover should additionally use the differential oracle and live-corpus relevance/latency evidence. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs:113-141] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:89-131]\n15: \n16: ## Ruled Out\n17: \n18: - Calling the database \"unfinished\": the storage, publication, query, hydration, telemetry, and operator machinery is implemented and tested.\n19: - Flipping `legacy` to `persistent` as the entire wiring plan: it would point clean checkouts at a missing publication pointer.\n20: \n21: ## Dead Ends\n22: \n23: - Treating feature richness as proof of default-path value. The vector/cursor/relationship machinery is capability supply; observed consumer demand remains separate.\n24: \n25: ## Edge Cases\n26: \n27: - Ambiguous input: \"build and populate\" could commit a generated DB or bootstrap locally. Both remain viable, but either requires an explicit freshness/distribution owner.\n28: - Contradictory evidence: the implementation is deployable in isolation while the product integration is incomplete. This is not a code-quality contradiction; it is an ownership gap.\n29: - Missing dependencies: no production workload trace or committed DB artifact.\n30: - Partial success: readiness is established statically, not through a live full-corpus build in this write-restricted research lineage.\n31: \n32: ## Sources Consulted\n33: \n34: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs:1-357`\n35: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:1-147`\n36: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/indexer.mjs:1-480`\n37: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/schema.mjs:1-360`\n38: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:1-520`\n39: - `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/operator.mjs:1-268`\n40: \n41: ## Assessment\n42: \n43: - New information ratio: 0.85\n44: - Novelty justification: Five findings are new and one refines the consumer-demand result from iteration 1.\n45: - Questions addressed: persistent implementation completeness and exact default-path gap.\n46: - Questions answered: the implementation is mature, but no build/distribution/refresh owner or cutover evidence makes it a real default.\n47: - Confidence: high on static readiness; medium on operational effort until a full-corpus build and workload trace are measured.\n48: \n49: ## Reflection\n50: \n51: - What worked and why: separating implementation completeness from integration completeness resolved the apparent \"built but unused\" paradox.\n52: - What did not work and why: reading only the first indexer segment did not expose the full build function, but the operator and README independently establish its lifecycle and invocation contract.\n53: - What I would do differently: quantify current benefits and recurring costs before treating the missing lifecycle as work worth funding.\n54: \n55: ## Recommended Next Focus\n56: \n57: Measure the economic case from available evidence: corpus size, legacy query work, existing benchmark claims, DB build/repair burden, and missing relevance/workload validation.\n\n(End of file - total 57 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 2: Persistent Backend Readiness and Missing Wiring\n\n## Focus\n\nAssess whether the database is merely a sketch or a deployable projection, then enumerate what still separates it from a safe default.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. The persistent implementation is technically substantial, not a stub: schema v2 contains normalized style/provenance/artifact/facet/section tables, external-content FTS5, embeddings/jobs/vectors, relationships, immutable corpus generations, and indexes. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/schema.mjs:35-269]\n2. Publication and rollback are implemented around immutable generation files plus an atomic `.current.json` manifest pointer. The operator supports `status`, `build`, `cutover`, `rollback`, and vector `repair`, retaining current plus one rollback generation. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:6-49] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/operator.mjs:75-185] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/operator.mjs:207-247]\n3. Query semantics exceed today's consumer needs: structured, FTS5, and optional vector lanes feed deterministic weighted RRF, generation-bound cursors, attribution, and channel-local degradation. Consumers currently ask for at most five reference cards and do not supply evidence that vector search or pagination is required. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:13-25] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:168-294] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:364-510] [INFERENCE: iteration 1 consumer evidence]\n4. The code deliberately avoids implicit construction: `buildStyleDatabase()` is never invoked by query or hydrate, and the operator requires an explicit corpus path. Therefore changing the mode default alone would fail on a clean checkout because neither the default SQLite artifact nor its pointer exists. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:40-43] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/operator.mjs:213-226] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/schema.mjs:11-23]\n5. A production cutover needs more than one successful build: it needs a refresh owner tied to corpus extraction/update, artifact distribution or deterministic local bootstrap, status/repair observability, and a failure policy. No such default-path lifecycle is visible in the facade or operator; reads fail closed rather than auto-building, which is correct for integrity but leaves operations unowned. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-49] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs:144-166]\n6. Shadow mode is a useful migration gate but its parity comparison intentionally tolerates generation hashes, content hashes, score values, and ranking mode. It checks projected cards and eligibility, not strict rank/score equivalence; default cutover should additionally use the differential oracle and live-corpus relevance/latency evidence. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs:113-141] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:89-131]\n\n## Ruled Out\n\n- Calling the database \"unfinished\": the storage, publication, query, hydration, telemetry, and operator machinery is implemented and tested.\n- Flipping `legacy` to `persistent` as the entire wiring plan: it would point clean checkouts at a missing publication pointer.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-002.md","text":"# Iteration 2: Persistent Backend Readiness and Missing Wiring\n\n## Focus\n\nAssess whether the database is merely a sketch or a deployable projection, then enumerate what still separates it from a safe default.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. The persistent implementation is technically substantial, not a stub: schema v2 contains normalized style/provenance/artifact/facet/section tables, external-content FTS5, embeddings/jobs/vectors, relationships, immutable corpus generations, and indexes. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/schema.mjs:35-269]\n2. Publication and rollback are implemented around immutable generation files plus an atomic `.current.json` manifest pointer. The operator supports `status`, `build`, `cutover`, `rollback`, and vector `repair`, retaining current plus one rollback generation. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:6-49] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/operator.mjs:75-185] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/operator.mjs:207-247]\n3. Query semantics exceed today's consumer needs: structured, FTS5, and optional vector lanes feed deterministic weighted RRF, generation-bound cursors, attribution, and channel-local degradation. Consumers currently ask for at most five reference cards and do not supply evidence that vector search or pagination is required. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:13-25] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:168-294] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:364-510] [INFERENCE: iteration 1 consumer evidence]\n4. The code deliberately avoids implicit construction: `buildStyleDatabase()` is never invoked by query or hydrate, and the operator requires an explicit corpus path. Therefore changing the mode default alone would fail on a clean checkout because neither the default SQLite artifact nor its pointer exists. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:40-43] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/operator.mjs:213-226] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/schema.mjs:11-23]\n5. A production cutover needs more than one successful build: it needs a refresh owner tied to corpus extraction/update, artifact distribution or deterministic local bootstrap, status/repair observability, and a failure policy. No such default-path lifecycle is visible in the facade or operator; reads fail closed rather than auto-building, which is correct for integrity but leaves operations unowned. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-49] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs:144-166]\n6. Shadow mode is a useful migration gate but its parity comparison intentionally tolerates generation hashes, content hashes, score values, and ranking mode. It checks projected cards and eligibility, not strict rank/score equivalence; default cutover should additionally use the differential oracle and live-corpus relevance/latency evidence. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs:113-141] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:89-131]\n\n## Ruled Out\n\n- Calling the database \"unfinished\": the storage, publication, query, hydration, telemetry, and operator machinery is implemented and tested.\n- Flipping `legacy` to `persistent` as the entire wiring plan: it would point clean checkouts at a missing publication pointer.\n\n## Dead Ends\n\n- Treating feature richness as proof of default-path value. The vector/cursor/relationship machinery is capability supply; observed consumer demand remains separate.\n\n## Edge Cases\n\n- Ambiguous input: \"build and populate\" could commit a generated DB or bootstrap locally. Both remain viable, but either requires an explicit freshness/distribution owner.\n- Contradictory evidence: the implementation is deployable in isolation while the product integration is incomplete. This is not a code-quality contradiction; it is an ownership gap.\n- Missing dependencies: no production workload trace or committed DB artifact.\n- Partial success: readiness is established statically, not through a live full-corpus build in this write-restricted research lineage.\n\n## Sources Consulted\n\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs:1-357`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:1-147`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/indexer.mjs:1-480`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/schema.mjs:1-360`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/retrieval.mjs:1-520`\n- `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/operator.mjs:1-268`\n\n## Assessment\n\n- New information ratio: 0.85\n- Novelty justification: Five findings are new and one refines the consumer-demand result from iteration 1.\n- Questions addressed: persistent implementation completeness and exact default-path gap.\n- Questions answered: the implementation is mature, but no build/distribution/refresh owner or cutover evidence makes it a real default.\n- Confidence: high on static readiness; medium on operational effort until a full-corpus build and workload trace are measured.\n\n## Reflection\n\n- What worked and why: separating implementation completeness from integration completeness resolved the apparent \"built but unused\" paradox.\n- What did not work and why: reading only the first indexer segment did not expose the full build function, but the operator and README independently establish its lifecycle and invocation contract.\n- What I would do differently: quantify current benefits and recurring costs before treating the missing lifecycle as work worth funding.\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\n\nMeasure the economic case from available evidence: corpus size, legacy query work, existing benchmark claims, DB build/repair burden, and missing relevance/workload validation.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":57,"totalLines":57,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-002.md","time":{"start":1784623663181,"end":1784623663263}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0214130f072a5df6016a5f322f03948191aad40850eca91600"}},"id":"prt_f83dc0848001uWWemavBHTypIH","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","messageID":"msg_f83dbb4c8001mzy7FKcjG5lS24"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784623663373,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_3c36jiJPPoGqO3ooyOp9YNmk","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-004.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-004.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 4: Decision Framework and Promotion Gates\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: \n5: Convert the evidence into a weighted, reversible choice. Stress-test the argument that recent implementation effort or future capabilities should override present consumer fit.\n6: \n7: ## Findings\n8: \n9: 1. Present consumers do not use persistent-only request features. A scoped search for `queryVector`, `vectorProfile`, `cursor`, `candidateK`, and channel controls found those tokens in database/oracle/tests, not in the four corpus consumer calls. The future JS-capabilities packet explicitly keeps new features shadow/flag-gated and away from the default path. [SOURCE: scoped Grep result over `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-*`] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/002-js-capabilities/spec.md:55-79] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/002-js-capabilities/spec.md:99-132]\n10: 2. The roadmap's own governance favors conditional adoption: native work requires a named measured SLO crossing and accepts \"no Rust\" as a valid outcome; growth work is out of scope at today's 1,290 bundles. The same evidence discipline should apply one level earlier to making SQLite the default. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/003-measured-native/spec.md:54-74] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/003-measured-native/spec.md:95-123] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/004-growth/spec.md:55-83]\n11: 3. Weighted present-state score (1=poor, 5=strong) favors formal shelving 85/100 over wiring 54/100:\n12: \n13: | Criterion | Weight | Wire | Shelf | Evidence basis |\n14: |---|---:|---:|---:|---|\n15: | Current consumer fit | 25 | 3 | 5 | Shared bounded facade works; no persistent-only consumer demand |\n16: | Measured material value | 20 | 1 | 4 | Only directional 20-style timing; no workload/SLO/relevance proof |\n17: | Operational simplicity/ownership | 20 | 1 | 5 | Wire adds publication/freshness/migration/repair state |\n18: | Integrity and rollback | 15 | 5 | 4 | DB generation model is stronger; flat manifest guards are simpler but less atomic |\n19: | Future capability leverage | 10 | 5 | 2 | DB enables vectors/cursors/multimodal roadmap |\n20: | Reversibility and option value | 10 | 3 | 4 | Shelf can recover from Git; wire creates consumers and generated-state coupling |\n21: \n22:    Weighted formula is `sum(weight * rating / 5)`. Ratings are decision aids, not measurements; changing reasonable ratings does not close the 31-point gap without assuming future demand or unmeasured materiality. [INFERENCE: iterations 1-3]\n23: 4. Recommendation: formally shelve the SQLite runtime now and make the flat-file engine the sole supported path. \"Formally\" means remove live mode claims and dormant runtime ownership, not merely retain `legacy` as a default beside unused alternatives. Recent DB work is a sunk cost; its best return is captured design evidence and Git history, not indefinite maintenance. [INFERENCE: weighted framework and gap-analysis requirement at .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/gap-analysis.md:168-171]\n24: 5. Reactivation should require all gates, not any one gate: (a) representative legacy workload with query count and warm/cold p50/p95; (b) an approved SLO breach or persistent improvement of at least 30% and 25 ms absolute at p95; (c) full-corpus build size/time and deterministic refresh ownership; (d) 100% facade/refusal/generation parity plus no statistically material relevance regression on human judgments; (e) successful shadow operation and rollback; and (f) either two consumers needing a persistent-only capability or a proven latency need. These are proposed gates, not observed results. [INFERENCE: current evidence gaps and roadmap gate patterns]\n25: 6. Wiring remains a valid contingent plan, but only after the gates clear. The existing facade, operator, telemetry, oracle, and generation machinery make later revival technically credible; they do not justify retaining a dormant production surface indefinitely. [SOURCE: iterations 1-3]\n26: \n27: ## Ruled Out\n28: \n29: - Keep all database code indefinitely \"for optionality\": Git history and decision artifacts preserve optionality without active maintenance claims.\n30: - Promote because Phase 0 was recently built: sunk cost is not present demand.\n31: - Promote on one fast benchmark: operations, parity, relevance, and ownership are conjunctive gates.\n32: \n33: ## Dead Ends\n34: \n35: - A compromise where `legacy` remains default and `shadow|persistent` remain undocumented-but-live does not remediate the identified dormancy gap; it preserves the current ambiguity.\n36: \n37: ## Edge Cases\n38: \n39: - Ambiguous input: \"shelve\" might mean leave code dormant. This framework defines it more strongly: remove supported runtime surface while preserving evidence and recoverability in version control.\n40: - Contradictory evidence: the database scores highest on integrity and future leverage but still loses because current demand, evidence, and ownership carry greater weight.\n41: - Missing dependencies: operator risk tolerance could alter weights, but the result is robust unless future capability is weighted above current use and operations combined.\n42: - Partial success: exact promotion thresholds require operator approval; proposed values are explicit starting gates.\n43: \n44: ## Sources Consulted\n45: \n46: - Detached state/config/strategy through iteration 3.\n47: - Scoped consumer feature-token search.\n48: - `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/002-js-capabilities/spec.md`\n49: - `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/003-measured-native/spec.md`\n50: - `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/004-growth/spec.md`\n51: - Parent gap analysis.\n52: \n53: ## Assessment\n54: \n55: - New information ratio: 0.58\n56: - Novelty justification: The scoring model, formal shelf definition, and conjunctive promotion gates are new; underlying evidence is synthesized from prior iterations.\n57: - Questions addressed: decision criteria and thresholds.\n58: - Questions answered: current evidence favors formal shelving 85/100 to 54/100, with explicit gates for reversal.\n59: - Confidence: medium-high; scoring contains judgment, but the direction is robust to moderate weight/rating changes.\n60: \n61: ## Reflection\n62: \n63: - What worked and why: weighted scoring made value judgments inspectable and exposed where a pro-wire conclusion would depend on future assumptions.\n64: - What did not work and why: the broad wildcard scope in the feature-token search also surfaced database internals; the absence claim was therefore limited to verified consumer call sites rather than the whole glob output.\n65: - What I would do differently: final iteration should produce both executable plans so the recommendation remains useful even if the operator chooses the lower-scoring option.\n66: \n67: ## Recommended Next Focus\n68: \n69: Adversarially validate the recommendation and produce complete wiring and deprecation plans, including sequencing, rollback, preserved assets, and roadmap/spec consequences.\n\n(End of file - total 69 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 4: Decision Framework and Promotion Gates\n\n## Focus\n\nConvert the evidence into a weighted, reversible choice. Stress-test the argument that recent implementation effort or future capabilities should override present consumer fit.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. Present consumers do not use persistent-only request features. A scoped search for `queryVector`, `vectorProfile`, `cursor`, `candidateK`, and channel controls found those tokens in database/oracle/tests, not in the four corpus consumer calls. The future JS-capabilities packet explicitly keeps new features shadow/flag-gated and away from the default path. [SOURCE: scoped Grep result over `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-*`] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/002-js-capabilities/spec.md:55-79] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/002-js-capabilities/spec.md:99-132]\n2. The roadmap's own governance favors conditional adoption: native work requires a named measured SLO crossing and accepts \"no Rust\" as a valid outcome; growth work is out of scope at today's 1,290 bundles. The same evidence discipline should apply one level earlier to making SQLite the default. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/003-measured-native/spec.md:54-74] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/003-measured-native/spec.md:95-123] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/004-growth/spec.md:55-83]\n3. Weighted present-state score (1=poor, 5=strong) favors formal shelving 85/100 over wiring 54/100:\n\n| Criterion | Weight | Wire | Shelf | Evidence basis |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|---|\n| Current consumer fit | 25 | 3 | 5 | Shared bounded facade works; no persistent-only consumer demand |\n| Measured material value | 20 | 1 | 4 | Only directional 20-style timing; no workload/SLO/relevance proof |\n| Operational simplicity/ownership | 20 | 1 | 5 | Wire adds publication/freshness/migration/repair state |\n| Integrity and rollback | 15 | 5 | 4 | DB generation model is stronger; flat manifest guards are simpler but less atomic |\n| Future capability leverage | 10 | 5 | 2 | DB enables vectors/cursors/multimodal roadmap |\n| Reversibility and option value | 10 | 3 | 4 | Shelf can recover from Git; wire creates consumers and generated-state coupling |","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-004.md","text":"# Iteration 4: Decision Framework and Promotion Gates\n\n## Focus\n\nConvert the evidence into a weighted, reversible choice. Stress-test the argument that recent implementation effort or future capabilities should override present consumer fit.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. Present consumers do not use persistent-only request features. A scoped search for `queryVector`, `vectorProfile`, `cursor`, `candidateK`, and channel controls found those tokens in database/oracle/tests, not in the four corpus consumer calls. The future JS-capabilities packet explicitly keeps new features shadow/flag-gated and away from the default path. [SOURCE: scoped Grep result over `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-*`] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/002-js-capabilities/spec.md:55-79] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/002-js-capabilities/spec.md:99-132]\n2. The roadmap's own governance favors conditional adoption: native work requires a named measured SLO crossing and accepts \"no Rust\" as a valid outcome; growth work is out of scope at today's 1,290 bundles. The same evidence discipline should apply one level earlier to making SQLite the default. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/003-measured-native/spec.md:54-74] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/003-measured-native/spec.md:95-123] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/004-growth/spec.md:55-83]\n3. Weighted present-state score (1=poor, 5=strong) favors formal shelving 85/100 over wiring 54/100:\n\n| Criterion | Weight | Wire | Shelf | Evidence basis |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|---|\n| Current consumer fit | 25 | 3 | 5 | Shared bounded facade works; no persistent-only consumer demand |\n| Measured material value | 20 | 1 | 4 | Only directional 20-style timing; no workload/SLO/relevance proof |\n| Operational simplicity/ownership | 20 | 1 | 5 | Wire adds publication/freshness/migration/repair state |\n| Integrity and rollback | 15 | 5 | 4 | DB generation model is stronger; flat manifest guards are simpler but less atomic |\n| Future capability leverage | 10 | 5 | 2 | DB enables vectors/cursors/multimodal roadmap |\n| Reversibility and option value | 10 | 3 | 4 | Shelf can recover from Git; wire creates consumers and generated-state coupling |\n\n   Weighted formula is `sum(weight * rating / 5)`. Ratings are decision aids, not measurements; changing reasonable ratings does not close the 31-point gap without assuming future demand or unmeasured materiality. [INFERENCE: iterations 1-3]\n4. Recommendation: formally shelve the SQLite runtime now and make the flat-file engine the sole supported path. \"Formally\" means remove live mode claims and dormant runtime ownership, not merely retain `legacy` as a default beside unused alternatives. Recent DB work is a sunk cost; its best return is captured design evidence and Git history, not indefinite maintenance. [INFERENCE: weighted framework and gap-analysis requirement at .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/gap-analysis.md:168-171]\n5. Reactivation should require all gates, not any one gate: (a) representative legacy workload with query count and warm/cold p50/p95; (b) an approved SLO breach or persistent improvement of at least 30% and 25 ms absolute at p95; (c) full-corpus build size/time and deterministic refresh ownership; (d) 100% facade/refusal/generation parity plus no statistically material relevance regression on human judgments; (e) successful shadow operation and rollback; and (f) either two consumers needing a persistent-only capability or a proven latency need. These are proposed gates, not observed results. [INFERENCE: current evidence gaps and roadmap gate patterns]\n6. Wiring remains a valid contingent plan, but only after the gates clear. The existing facade, operator, telemetry, oracle, and generation machinery make later revival technically credible; they do not justify retaining a dormant production surface indefinitely. [SOURCE: iterations 1-3]\n\n## Ruled Out\n\n- Keep all database code indefinitely \"for optionality\": Git history and decision artifacts preserve optionality without active maintenance claims.\n- Promote because Phase 0 was recently built: sunk cost is not present demand.\n- Promote on one fast benchmark: operations, parity, relevance, and ownership are conjunctive gates.\n\n## Dead Ends\n\n- A compromise where `legacy` remains default and `shadow|persistent` remain undocumented-but-live does not remediate the identified dormancy gap; it preserves the current ambiguity.\n\n## Edge Cases\n\n- Ambiguous input: \"shelve\" might mean leave code dormant. This framework defines it more strongly: remove supported runtime surface while preserving evidence and recoverability in version control.\n- Contradictory evidence: the database scores highest on integrity and future leverage but still loses because current demand, evidence, and ownership carry greater weight.\n- Missing dependencies: operator risk tolerance could alter weights, but the result is robust unless future capability is weighted above current use and operations combined.\n- Partial success: exact promotion thresholds require operator approval; proposed values are explicit starting gates.\n\n## Sources Consulted\n\n- Detached state/config/strategy through iteration 3.\n- Scoped consumer feature-token search.\n- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/002-js-capabilities/spec.md`\n- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/003-measured-native/spec.md`\n- `.opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/004-growth/spec.md`\n- Parent gap analysis.\n\n## Assessment\n\n- New information ratio: 0.58\n- Novelty justification: The scoring model, formal shelf definition, and conjunctive promotion gates are new; underlying evidence is synthesized from prior iterations.\n- Questions addressed: decision criteria and thresholds.\n- Questions answered: current evidence favors formal shelving 85/100 to 54/100, with explicit gates for reversal.\n- Confidence: medium-high; scoring contains judgment, but the direction is robust to moderate weight/rating changes.\n\n## Reflection\n\n- What worked and why: weighted scoring made value judgments inspectable and exposed where a pro-wire conclusion would depend on future assumptions.\n- What did not work and why: the broad wildcard scope in the feature-token search also surfaced database internals; the absence claim was therefore limited to verified consumer call sites rather than the whole glob output.\n- What I would do differently: final iteration should produce both executable plans so the recommendation remains useful even if the operator chooses the lower-scoring option.\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\n\nAdversarially validate the recommendation and produce complete wiring and deprecation plans, including sequencing, rollback, preserved assets, and roadmap/spec consequences.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":69,"totalLines":69,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-004.md","time":{"start":1784623663353,"end":1784623663365}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0214130f072a5df6016a5f322f03b08191aef767eed5283857"}},"id":"prt_f83dc0877001mxDPHGeMhyETP1","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","messageID":"msg_f83dbb4c8001mzy7FKcjG5lS24"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784623663410,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_au6RiAG7KPQDwPv4cX6hdq4y","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 5: Adversarial Validation and Both Execution Plans\n2: \n3: ## Focus\n4: \n5: Try to overturn the shelf recommendation, map the live-code blast radius, and deliver complete reversible plans for either operator choice.\n6: \n7: ## Findings\n8: \n9: 1. Shelving has a bounded live-code blast radius. In executable `.mjs`, database-mode references outside `_db` occur only in `_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs`, `_engine/style-library.mjs`, and the DB adapter tests. The four corpus modules have no direct DB imports, so their API need not change. [SOURCE: scoped Grep for `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE|styleDatabaseMode|persistent-adapter|_db/...` under `.opencode/**/*.mjs`]\n10: 2. The flat engine is not an unsafe fallback. Its dedicated suite covers byte-stable non-writing checks, eligibility-first behavior, source-scan fallback, generation/path/hash hydration guards, invalidation, and proof behavior. It rejects poisoned derived fields and stale manifests before query, and enforces generation, rights, byte, and path-escape guards during hydration. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/index.mjs:1-10] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/check-stable.test.mjs:14-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/hydrate-guard.test.mjs:20-163]\n11: 3. The strongest pro-wire counterargument is repeat-query cost: the legacy engine reconstructs freshness and disposable search repeatedly, while the persistent implementation already has safe publication and richer retrieval. Wiring now would be rational if real design sessions issue enough queries to breach an approved latency SLO and a clean-checkout publication lifecycle is already funded. Neither condition is evidenced, so the counterargument does not overturn the recommendation. [SOURCE: iterations 1-3]\n12: 4. **Wiring plan if kept:** (a) preserve the facade and flat files as content authority; (b) choose and document clean-checkout distribution, either checked-in immutable generation under a size budget or mandatory install/prewarm build; (c) build and publish a real full-corpus generation, record size/build telemetry, and verify status/rollback; (d) add authoritative refresh ownership after corpus extraction plus periodic reconciliation; (e) run legacy/persistent shadow against representative consumer requests, strict oracle/refusal/generation parity, and human relevance judgments; (f) meet every promotion gate from iteration 4; (g) switch the adapter default to persistent while retaining an explicit legacy kill switch for a bounded observation window; (h) monitor pointer/generation/vector failures and latency; (i) remove dual-mode code only after the window. Rollback is one manifest-pointer reversal plus the legacy kill switch. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-87] [SOURCE: iteration-004.md]\n13: 5. **Deprecation plan if shelved:** (a) record the decision and mark the 015 roadmap and children superseded/shelved rather than planned; (b) retain 013/015/this research as design evidence and reactivation gates; (c) remove `_db`, DB-only tests/goldens/seeds, `persistent-adapter.mjs`, `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE`, `styleDatabaseMode`, CLI `--backend/--database`, and DB README claims; (d) route `runQuery`/`runHydrate` directly to the existing flat implementation; (e) keep the retrieval manifest because it is the flat engine's generation/freshness contract, then rename/restructure it only in the separate filesystem packet; (f) run the flat engine suite plus all four corpus suites and verify no DB imports/modes/artifacts remain; (g) remove planned DB evolution from active navigation. Rollback is a targeted Git revert; no data migration exists because no real DB was published. [SOURCE: scoped dependency Grep] [SOURCE: scoped retrieval-manifest Grep] [SOURCE: gap-analysis.md:72-105]\n14: 6. Preserving dormant runtime code is not a safe middle path. It leaves two supported semantics, mode-dependent failures, roadmap obligations, and documentation drift while providing no user-visible default capability. Preserve knowledge, not an unowned live surface. [INFERENCE: iterations 2-5]\n15: \n16: ## Ruled Out\n17: \n18: - Shelf by deleting `_retrieval-manifest.json`: it belongs to and protects the flat engine.\n19: - Shelf while leaving environment/CLI switches live: that is the current dormant state, not remediation.\n20: - Wire by lazy query-time build: integrity-sensitive reads should not unexpectedly walk and mutate the corpus.\n21: - Wire without a clean-checkout distribution decision: a missing pointer would make default consumers fail.\n22: \n23: ## Dead Ends\n24: \n25: - No evidence overturns the shelf recommendation. The remaining pro-wire case is explicitly contingent on future measured workload and funded lifecycle ownership.\n26: \n27: ## Edge Cases\n28: \n29: - Ambiguous input: whether to preserve generic canonicalizer/telemetry/oracle modules. They are currently DB-owned and have no independent consumer; preserve their design in docs/Git, not live source, unless a concrete reuse is identified before removal.\n30: - Contradictory evidence: the recently built foundation is high quality, but removing it can still be correct because quality does not create demand.\n31: - Missing dependencies: the operator must approve final deletion scope and the proposed numeric reactivation thresholds.\n32: - Partial success: plans are implementation-ready at decision level but intentionally do not enumerate every deleted file.\n33: \n34: ## Sources Consulted\n35: \n36: - Detached state/config/strategy through iteration 4.\n37: - Scoped DB-mode/import dependency search.\n38: - Scoped retrieval-manifest/build ownership search.\n39: - Flat engine test index, stable-check tests, and hydration-guard tests.\n40: \n41: ## Assessment\n42: \n43: - New information ratio: 0.43\n44: - Novelty justification: The bounded blast radius and both sequenced execution plans are new; the final recommendation consolidates prior evidence.\n45: - Questions addressed: safe wiring and deprecation plans.\n46: - Questions answered: both paths are reversible; shelving is lower-risk and better supported now.\n47: - Confidence: high on recommendation and blast radius; medium on exact implementation scope pending a dedicated plan/review.\n48: \n49: ## Reflection\n50: \n51: - What worked and why: dependency search confirmed that storage choice is isolated enough for a clean shelf without consumer rewrites.\n52: - What did not work and why: no runtime trace exists to test the strongest pro-wire hypothesis; it remains a reactivation gate.\n53: - What I would do differently: if the operator chooses wire despite the recommendation, make the first implementation task measurement and distribution proof, not default flipping.\n54: \n55: ## Recommended Next Focus\n56: \n57: Synthesize the five iterations into the final decision report. Stop reason: `maxIterationsReached`.\n\n(End of file - total 57 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 5: Adversarial Validation and Both Execution Plans\n\n## Focus\n\nTry to overturn the shelf recommendation, map the live-code blast radius, and deliver complete reversible plans for either operator choice.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. Shelving has a bounded live-code blast radius. In executable `.mjs`, database-mode references outside `_db` occur only in `_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs`, `_engine/style-library.mjs`, and the DB adapter tests. The four corpus modules have no direct DB imports, so their API need not change. [SOURCE: scoped Grep for `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE|styleDatabaseMode|persistent-adapter|_db/...` under `.opencode/**/*.mjs`]\n2. The flat engine is not an unsafe fallback. Its dedicated suite covers byte-stable non-writing checks, eligibility-first behavior, source-scan fallback, generation/path/hash hydration guards, invalidation, and proof behavior. It rejects poisoned derived fields and stale manifests before query, and enforces generation, rights, byte, and path-escape guards during hydration. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/index.mjs:1-10] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/check-stable.test.mjs:14-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/hydrate-guard.test.mjs:20-163]\n3. The strongest pro-wire counterargument is repeat-query cost: the legacy engine reconstructs freshness and disposable search repeatedly, while the persistent implementation already has safe publication and richer retrieval. Wiring now would be rational if real design sessions issue enough queries to breach an approved latency SLO and a clean-checkout publication lifecycle is already funded. Neither condition is evidenced, so the counterargument does not overturn the recommendation. [SOURCE: iterations 1-3]\n4. **Wiring plan if kept:** (a) preserve the facade and flat files as content authority; (b) choose and document clean-checkout distribution, either checked-in immutable generation under a size budget or mandatory install/prewarm build; (c) build and publish a real full-corpus generation, record size/build telemetry, and verify status/rollback; (d) add authoritative refresh ownership after corpus extraction plus periodic reconciliation; (e) run legacy/persistent shadow against representative consumer requests, strict oracle/refusal/generation parity, and human relevance judgments; (f) meet every promotion gate from iteration 4; (g) switch the adapter default to persistent while retaining an explicit legacy kill switch for a bounded observation window; (h) monitor pointer/generation/vector failures and latency; (i) remove dual-mode code only after the window. Rollback is one manifest-pointer reversal plus the legacy kill switch. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-87] [SOURCE: iteration-004.md]\n5. **Deprecation plan if shelved:** (a) record the decision and mark the 015 roadmap and children superseded/shelved rather than planned; (b) retain 013/015/this research as design evidence and reactivation gates; (c) remove `_db`, DB-only tests/goldens/seeds, `persistent-adapter.mjs`, `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE`, `styleDatabaseMode`, CLI `--backend/--database`, and DB README claims; (d) route `runQuery`/`runHydrate` directly to the existing flat implementation; (e) keep the retrieval manifest because it is the flat engine's generation/freshness contract, then rename/restructure it only in the separate filesystem packet; (f) run the flat engine suite plus all four corpus suites and verify no DB imports/modes/artifacts remain; (g) remove planned DB evolution from active navigation. Rollback is a targeted Git revert; no data migration exists because no real DB was published. [SOURCE: scoped dependency Grep] [SOURCE: scoped retrieval-manifest Grep] [SOURCE: gap-analysis.md:72-105]\n6. Preserving dormant runtime code is not a safe middle path. It leaves two supported semantics, mode-dependent failures, roadmap obligations, and documentation drift while providing no user-visible default capability. Preserve knowledge, not an unowned live surface. [INFERENCE: iterations 2-5]\n\n## Ruled Out\n\n- Shelf by deleting `_retrieval-manifest.json`: it belongs to and protects the flat engine.\n- Shelf while leaving environment/CLI switches live: that is the current dormant state, not remediation.\n- Wire by lazy query-time build: integrity-sensitive reads should not unexpectedly walk and mutate the corpus.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md","text":"# Iteration 5: Adversarial Validation and Both Execution Plans\n\n## Focus\n\nTry to overturn the shelf recommendation, map the live-code blast radius, and deliver complete reversible plans for either operator choice.\n\n## Findings\n\n1. Shelving has a bounded live-code blast radius. In executable `.mjs`, database-mode references outside `_db` occur only in `_engine/persistent-adapter.mjs`, `_engine/style-library.mjs`, and the DB adapter tests. The four corpus modules have no direct DB imports, so their API need not change. [SOURCE: scoped Grep for `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE|styleDatabaseMode|persistent-adapter|_db/...` under `.opencode/**/*.mjs`]\n2. The flat engine is not an unsafe fallback. Its dedicated suite covers byte-stable non-writing checks, eligibility-first behavior, source-scan fallback, generation/path/hash hydration guards, invalidation, and proof behavior. It rejects poisoned derived fields and stale manifests before query, and enforces generation, rights, byte, and path-escape guards during hydration. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/index.mjs:1-10] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/check-stable.test.mjs:14-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_engine/__tests__/hydrate-guard.test.mjs:20-163]\n3. The strongest pro-wire counterargument is repeat-query cost: the legacy engine reconstructs freshness and disposable search repeatedly, while the persistent implementation already has safe publication and richer retrieval. Wiring now would be rational if real design sessions issue enough queries to breach an approved latency SLO and a clean-checkout publication lifecycle is already funded. Neither condition is evidenced, so the counterargument does not overturn the recommendation. [SOURCE: iterations 1-3]\n4. **Wiring plan if kept:** (a) preserve the facade and flat files as content authority; (b) choose and document clean-checkout distribution, either checked-in immutable generation under a size budget or mandatory install/prewarm build; (c) build and publish a real full-corpus generation, record size/build telemetry, and verify status/rollback; (d) add authoritative refresh ownership after corpus extraction plus periodic reconciliation; (e) run legacy/persistent shadow against representative consumer requests, strict oracle/refusal/generation parity, and human relevance judgments; (f) meet every promotion gate from iteration 4; (g) switch the adapter default to persistent while retaining an explicit legacy kill switch for a bounded observation window; (h) monitor pointer/generation/vector failures and latency; (i) remove dual-mode code only after the window. Rollback is one manifest-pointer reversal plus the legacy kill switch. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_db/README.md:27-87] [SOURCE: iteration-004.md]\n5. **Deprecation plan if shelved:** (a) record the decision and mark the 015 roadmap and children superseded/shelved rather than planned; (b) retain 013/015/this research as design evidence and reactivation gates; (c) remove `_db`, DB-only tests/goldens/seeds, `persistent-adapter.mjs`, `SK_DESIGN_STYLE_DB_MODE`, `styleDatabaseMode`, CLI `--backend/--database`, and DB README claims; (d) route `runQuery`/`runHydrate` directly to the existing flat implementation; (e) keep the retrieval manifest because it is the flat engine's generation/freshness contract, then rename/restructure it only in the separate filesystem packet; (f) run the flat engine suite plus all four corpus suites and verify no DB imports/modes/artifacts remain; (g) remove planned DB evolution from active navigation. Rollback is a targeted Git revert; no data migration exists because no real DB was published. [SOURCE: scoped dependency Grep] [SOURCE: scoped retrieval-manifest Grep] [SOURCE: gap-analysis.md:72-105]\n6. Preserving dormant runtime code is not a safe middle path. It leaves two supported semantics, mode-dependent failures, roadmap obligations, and documentation drift while providing no user-visible default capability. Preserve knowledge, not an unowned live surface. [INFERENCE: iterations 2-5]\n\n## Ruled Out\n\n- Shelf by deleting `_retrieval-manifest.json`: it belongs to and protects the flat engine.\n- Shelf while leaving environment/CLI switches live: that is the current dormant state, not remediation.\n- Wire by lazy query-time build: integrity-sensitive reads should not unexpectedly walk and mutate the corpus.\n- Wire without a clean-checkout distribution decision: a missing pointer would make default consumers fail.\n\n## Dead Ends\n\n- No evidence overturns the shelf recommendation. The remaining pro-wire case is explicitly contingent on future measured workload and funded lifecycle ownership.\n\n## Edge Cases\n\n- Ambiguous input: whether to preserve generic canonicalizer/telemetry/oracle modules. They are currently DB-owned and have no independent consumer; preserve their design in docs/Git, not live source, unless a concrete reuse is identified before removal.\n- Contradictory evidence: the recently built foundation is high quality, but removing it can still be correct because quality does not create demand.\n- Missing dependencies: the operator must approve final deletion scope and the proposed numeric reactivation thresholds.\n- Partial success: plans are implementation-ready at decision level but intentionally do not enumerate every deleted file.\n\n## Sources Consulted\n\n- Detached state/config/strategy through iteration 4.\n- Scoped DB-mode/import dependency search.\n- Scoped retrieval-manifest/build ownership search.\n- Flat engine test index, stable-check tests, and hydration-guard tests.\n\n## Assessment\n\n- New information ratio: 0.43\n- Novelty justification: The bounded blast radius and both sequenced execution plans are new; the final recommendation consolidates prior evidence.\n- Questions addressed: safe wiring and deprecation plans.\n- Questions answered: both paths are reversible; shelving is lower-risk and better supported now.\n- Confidence: high on recommendation and blast radius; medium on exact implementation scope pending a dedicated plan/review.\n\n## Reflection\n\n- What worked and why: dependency search confirmed that storage choice is isolated enough for a clean shelf without consumer rewrites.\n- What did not work and why: no runtime trace exists to test the strongest pro-wire hypothesis; it remains a reactivation gate.\n- What I would do differently: if the operator chooses wire despite the recommendation, make the first implementation task measurement and distribution proof, not default flipping.\n\n## Recommended Next Focus\n\nSynthesize the five iterations into the final decision report. Stop reason: `maxIterationsReached`.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":57,"totalLines":57,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/iterations/iteration-005.md","time":{"start":1784623663383,"end":1784623663405}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0214130f072a5df6016a5f322f03bc81919592a24bf9077d0e"}},"id":"prt_f83dc0908001Gg0NbLNbjYTK7D","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","messageID":"msg_f83dbb4c8001mzy7FKcjG5lS24"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784623663483,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_dwUytuf35AqlcuLYOnX5mFKa","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Deep Research Strategy: Styles SQLite Database Fate\n2: \n3: ## 1. Research Topic\n4: \n5: Decide whether to fully wire and populate the dormant styles SQLite database as the default retrieval path or formally shelve it and retain the flat-file engine as the single source.\n6: \n7: ## 2. Non-Goals\n8: \n9: - Do not implement, remove, rename, or relocate styles code or data.\n10: - Do not modify the parent spec packet or any path outside this detached lineage.\n11: - Do not decide the separate interface-command rewrite or styles-directory naming questions.\n12: - Do not treat code existence or passing unit tests alone as proof of production need.\n13: \n14: ## 3. Stop Conditions\n15: \n16: - Complete exactly five iterations because `stopPolicy=max-iterations`.\n17: - Produce an evidence-backed recommendation, decision framework, keep-path wiring plan, and shelf-path deprecation plan.\n18: - Ground the recommendation in the four design-mode corpus consumers and current operational evidence.\n19: \n20: <!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n21: ## 4. Key Questions (Remaining)\n22: \n23: - [x] What contract and workload do design-interface, design-motion, design-audit, and design-foundations actually require from the styles library?\n24: - [x] How complete is the persistent implementation, and what exact work remains to make it the default and populate a real database?\n25: - [x] What measurable benefits justify SQLite at the present corpus size, and what recurring operational costs would default persistence introduce?\n26: - [x] Which decision criteria and thresholds should govern keep versus shelve?\n27: - [x] What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans, including rollback and preservation of useful evidence assets?\n28: <!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n29: \n30: <!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n31: ## 5. Answered Questions\n32: \n33: - The four consumers require a bounded, generation-safe `runQuery`/`runHydrate` facade and degrade safely when retrieval is unavailable; none requires SQLite specifically. (iteration 1)\n34: - The persistent implementation is mature, but a real default requires a published initial generation plus explicit build/distribution/refresh/repair ownership and live cutover evidence. (iteration 2)\n35: - Persistent selection avoids substantial repeat-query corpus I/O, but the only direct speed assertion is a 20-style fixture; present-scale materiality, workload demand, relevance quality, and lifecycle cost remain unmeasured. (iteration 3)\n36: - A weighted present-state framework scores formal shelving 85/100 versus wiring 54/100; reversal requires conjunctive workload, materiality, lifecycle, parity, relevance, shadow, rollback, and demand gates. (iteration 4)\n37: - Both paths are reversible: wiring requires distribution, build/refresh ownership, shadow/relevance gates, then cutover; shelving removes live DB code/modes and supersedes the roadmap while preserving the flat manifest and design evidence. (iteration 5)\n38: <!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n39: \n40: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n41: <!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n42: ## 6. What Worked\n43: \n44: - Consumer-to-facade tracing: showed that backend choice is isolated below all four corpus modules. (iteration 1)\n45: - Implementation-versus-integration separation: distinguished mature database code from the absent operational lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n46: - Evidence-class separation: distinguished correctness, directional speed, material speed, and product demand. (iteration 3)\n47: - Weighted scoring and sensitivity check: made judgment explicit and showed the result is not dependent on one criterion. (iteration 4)\n48: - Dependency and manifest-ownership scans: bounded the shelf blast radius and protected the flat engine's retrieval manifest. (iteration 5)\n49: <!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n50: \n51: <!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n52: ## 7. What Failed\n53: \n54: - Initial wildcard include search: returned no files because the path/include shape was too broad; replaced with an exact call-site search. (iteration 1)\n55: - First-segment indexer read: did not reach the build function, so operator and README evidence were used to triangulate the published lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n56: - Exact ROI modeling: blocked by the absent full-corpus database, workload trace, build timing, and human relevance set. (iteration 3)\n57: - Broad feature-token search: included database internals, so its absence claim was narrowed to consumer call sites. (iteration 4)\n58: - Pro-wire workload hypothesis: could not be tested because no runtime query trace exists; retained as a reactivation gate. (iteration 5)\n59: <!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n60: \n61: <!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n62: ## 8. Exhausted Approaches\n63: \n64: - Database-specific consumer rewrites: ruled out because all consumers already call the adapter-backed facade. (iteration 1)\n65: - SQLite as authoritative content storage: ruled out because hydration remains flat-file artifact access. (iteration 1)\n66: - Default flip without build/distribution: ruled out because clean checkouts have no pointer or generation file. (iteration 2)\n67: - Capability inventory as business justification: ruled out because consumer demand and measured value are separate. (iteration 2)\n68: - Synthetic 20-style timing as production justification: ruled out because it proves direction but records no materiality. (iteration 3)\n69: - Correctness suite as demand proof: ruled out because safety and usefulness are separate questions. (iteration 3)\n70: - Dormant-code optionality: ruled out because Git history and decision evidence preserve recovery without active runtime ownership. (iteration 4)\n71: - Sunk-cost promotion and one-benchmark promotion: ruled out by conjunctive promotion gates. (iteration 4)\n72: - Lazy query-time builds, shelf-with-live-switches, and deleting the flat retrieval manifest: ruled out as unsafe or non-remediating. (iteration 5)\n73: <!-- /ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n74: \n75: <!-- ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n76: ## 9. Ruled-Out Directions\n77: \n78: None yet.\n79: <!-- /ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n80: \n81: <!-- ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n82: ## 10. Carried-Forward Open Questions\n83: \n84: None yet.\n85: <!-- /ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n86: \n87: <!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n88: ## 11. Next Focus\n89: \n90: Synthesis complete after the fifth iteration; no further research focus.\n91: <!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n92: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n93: \n94: ## 12. Known Context\n95: \n96: - The gap analysis reports 1,290 style folders, no SQLite file, a `legacy` default, and four corpus modules routed through `_engine/style-library.mjs`. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/gap-analysis.md:22-89]\n97: - The database foundation packet reports 69 passing tests for generation manifests, telemetry, differential oracle, fixtures, and judgments, but identifies live-corpus telemetry and human relevance labels as unresolved. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:50-57] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:117-123]\n98: - `resource-map.md` is not present in the target spec folder; skipping the input coverage gate.\n99: \n100: ## 13. Research Boundaries\n101: \n102: - Maximum iterations: 5\n103: - Stop policy: max-iterations\n104: - Convergence threshold: 0.05, telemetry only before iteration 5\n105: - Allowed write root: this detached `sol-high-fast` lineage only\n106: - Per-iteration write set: one prompt, one narrative, one delta, one state-log append, then workflow-owned reducer projections\n\n(End of file - total 106 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Deep Research Strategy: Styles SQLite Database Fate\n\n## 1. Research Topic\n\nDecide whether to fully wire and populate the dormant styles SQLite database as the default retrieval path or formally shelve it and retain the flat-file engine as the single source.\n\n## 2. Non-Goals\n\n- Do not implement, remove, rename, or relocate styles code or data.\n- Do not modify the parent spec packet or any path outside this detached lineage.\n- Do not decide the separate interface-command rewrite or styles-directory naming questions.\n- Do not treat code existence or passing unit tests alone as proof of production need.\n\n## 3. Stop Conditions\n\n- Complete exactly five iterations because `stopPolicy=max-iterations`.\n- Produce an evidence-backed recommendation, decision framework, keep-path wiring plan, and shelf-path deprecation plan.\n- Ground the recommendation in the four design-mode corpus consumers and current operational evidence.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md","text":"# Deep Research Strategy: Styles SQLite Database Fate\n\n## 1. Research Topic\n\nDecide whether to fully wire and populate the dormant styles SQLite database as the default retrieval path or formally shelve it and retain the flat-file engine as the single source.\n\n## 2. Non-Goals\n\n- Do not implement, remove, rename, or relocate styles code or data.\n- Do not modify the parent spec packet or any path outside this detached lineage.\n- Do not decide the separate interface-command rewrite or styles-directory naming questions.\n- Do not treat code existence or passing unit tests alone as proof of production need.\n\n## 3. Stop Conditions\n\n- Complete exactly five iterations because `stopPolicy=max-iterations`.\n- Produce an evidence-backed recommendation, decision framework, keep-path wiring plan, and shelf-path deprecation plan.\n- Ground the recommendation in the four design-mode corpus consumers and current operational evidence.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n## 4. Key Questions (Remaining)\n\n- [x] What contract and workload do design-interface, design-motion, design-audit, and design-foundations actually require from the styles library?\n- [x] How complete is the persistent implementation, and what exact work remains to make it the default and populate a real database?\n- [x] What measurable benefits justify SQLite at the present corpus size, and what recurring operational costs would default persistence introduce?\n- [x] Which decision criteria and thresholds should govern keep versus shelve?\n- [x] What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans, including rollback and preservation of useful evidence assets?\n<!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n## 5. Answered Questions\n\n- The four consumers require a bounded, generation-safe `runQuery`/`runHydrate` facade and degrade safely when retrieval is unavailable; none requires SQLite specifically. (iteration 1)\n- The persistent implementation is mature, but a real default requires a published initial generation plus explicit build/distribution/refresh/repair ownership and live cutover evidence. (iteration 2)\n- Persistent selection avoids substantial repeat-query corpus I/O, but the only direct speed assertion is a 20-style fixture; present-scale materiality, workload demand, relevance quality, and lifecycle cost remain unmeasured. (iteration 3)\n- A weighted present-state framework scores formal shelving 85/100 versus wiring 54/100; reversal requires conjunctive workload, materiality, lifecycle, parity, relevance, shadow, rollback, and demand gates. (iteration 4)\n- Both paths are reversible: wiring requires distribution, build/refresh ownership, shadow/relevance gates, then cutover; shelving removes live DB code/modes and supersedes the roadmap while preserving the flat manifest and design evidence. (iteration 5)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n## 6. What Worked\n\n- Consumer-to-facade tracing: showed that backend choice is isolated below all four corpus modules. (iteration 1)\n- Implementation-versus-integration separation: distinguished mature database code from the absent operational lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n- Evidence-class separation: distinguished correctness, directional speed, material speed, and product demand. (iteration 3)\n- Weighted scoring and sensitivity check: made judgment explicit and showed the result is not dependent on one criterion. (iteration 4)\n- Dependency and manifest-ownership scans: bounded the shelf blast radius and protected the flat engine's retrieval manifest. (iteration 5)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n## 7. What Failed\n\n- Initial wildcard include search: returned no files because the path/include shape was too broad; replaced with an exact call-site search. (iteration 1)\n- First-segment indexer read: did not reach the build function, so operator and README evidence were used to triangulate the published lifecycle. (iteration 2)\n- Exact ROI modeling: blocked by the absent full-corpus database, workload trace, build timing, and human relevance set. (iteration 3)\n- Broad feature-token search: included database internals, so its absence claim was narrowed to consumer call sites. (iteration 4)\n- Pro-wire workload hypothesis: could not be tested because no runtime query trace exists; retained as a reactivation gate. (iteration 5)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n## 8. Exhausted Approaches\n\n- Database-specific consumer rewrites: ruled out because all consumers already call the adapter-backed facade. (iteration 1)\n- SQLite as authoritative content storage: ruled out because hydration remains flat-file artifact access. (iteration 1)\n- Default flip without build/distribution: ruled out because clean checkouts have no pointer or generation file. (iteration 2)\n- Capability inventory as business justification: ruled out because consumer demand and measured value are separate. (iteration 2)\n- Synthetic 20-style timing as production justification: ruled out because it proves direction but records no materiality. (iteration 3)\n- Correctness suite as demand proof: ruled out because safety and usefulness are separate questions. (iteration 3)\n- Dormant-code optionality: ruled out because Git history and decision evidence preserve recovery without active runtime ownership. (iteration 4)\n- Sunk-cost promotion and one-benchmark promotion: ruled out by conjunctive promotion gates. (iteration 4)\n- Lazy query-time builds, shelf-with-live-switches, and deleting the flat retrieval manifest: ruled out as unsafe or non-remediating. (iteration 5)\n<!-- /ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n## 9. Ruled-Out Directions\n\nNone yet.\n<!-- /ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n## 10. Carried-Forward Open Questions\n\nNone yet.\n<!-- /ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n## 11. Next Focus\n\nSynthesis complete after the fifth iteration; no further research focus.\n<!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n\n## 12. Known Context\n\n- The gap analysis reports 1,290 style folders, no SQLite file, a `legacy` default, and four corpus modules routed through `_engine/style-library.mjs`. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/gap-analysis.md:22-89]\n- The database foundation packet reports 69 passing tests for generation manifests, telemetry, differential oracle, fixtures, and judgments, but identifies live-corpus telemetry and human relevance labels as unresolved. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:50-57] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/015-styles-database-evolution/001-foundation/implementation-summary.md:117-123]\n- `resource-map.md` is not present in the target spec folder; skipping the input coverage gate.\n\n## 13. Research Boundaries\n\n- Maximum iterations: 5\n- Stop policy: max-iterations\n- Convergence threshold: 0.05, telemetry only before iteration 5\n- Allowed write root: this detached `sol-high-fast` lineage only\n- Per-iteration write set: one prompt, one narrative, one delta, one state-log append, then workflow-owned reducer projections","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":106,"totalLines":106,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/deep-research-strategy.md","time":{"start":1784623663415,"end":1784623663464}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0214130f072a5df6016a5f322f03c88191b6b8191970474601"}},"id":"prt_f83dc091d001M2txYcHAooXody","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","messageID":"msg_f83dbb4c8001mzy7FKcjG5lS24"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784623663483,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_8hxWGBWYSrUEQxxN0hUoEybl","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"openQuestions\": [],\n3:   \"resolvedQuestions\": [\n4:     {\"id\":\"q-consumers\",\"text\":\"What contract and workload do the four design-mode corpus consumers require?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":1,\"answer\":\"A bounded generation-safe query/hydration facade; no consumer requires SQLite specifically.\"},\n5:     {\"id\":\"q-readiness\",\"text\":\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":2,\"answer\":\"Technically mature, but missing a published artifact and an owned build/distribution/refresh/repair lifecycle plus live cutover evidence.\"},\n6:     {\"id\":\"q-economics\",\"text\":\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":3,\"answer\":\"It credibly removes repeat-query corpus I/O, but current-scale materiality and demand are unmeasured while defaulting introduces permanent publication, freshness, migration, monitoring, and repair ownership.\"},\n7:     {\"id\":\"q-criteria\",\"text\":\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":4,\"answer\":\"A weighted current-fit/materiality/operations/integrity/future/reversibility framework favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100; reactivation requires all evidence gates.\"},\n8:     {\"id\":\"q-plans\",\"text\":\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":5,\"answer\":\"Wire only through distribution/build/refresh/shadow/relevance/cutover gates; shelf by removing live DB modes/code and superseding its roadmap while preserving flat-manifest safety and design evidence.\"}\n9:   ],\n10:   \"keyFindings\": [\n11:     {\"id\":\"f-consumer-facade\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"All four corpus modules use the storage-neutral runQuery/runHydrate facade.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:181-207\",\"four corpus modules\"]},\n12:     {\"id\":\"f-content-authority\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Flat artifacts remain authoritative content under persistent selection.\",\"sources\":[\"consumer hydration calls\"]},\n13:     {\"id\":\"f-legacy-freshness-cost\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Legacy queries rebuild and compare the live corpus manifest on every call.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:123-159\"]},\n14:     {\"id\":\"f-db-mature\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"The persistent projection and operator machinery are technically mature.\",\"sources\":[\"schema.mjs:35-269\",\"retrieval.mjs:364-510\",\"operator.mjs:75-247\"]},\n15:     {\"id\":\"f-lifecycle-unowned\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"No default build, distribution, refresh, or repair owner exists.\",\"sources\":[\"README.md:40-49\",\"operator.mjs:213-226\"]},\n16:     {\"id\":\"f-shadow-bounded\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Shadow parity tolerates ranking and identity differences and is not a sufficient cutover gate alone.\",\"sources\":[\"persistent-adapter.mjs:113-141\"]},\n17:     {\"id\":\"f-benefit-directional\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Persistent selection is directionally faster, but current-scale materiality is unmeasured.\",\"sources\":[\"adapter.test.mjs:107-132\",\"rank-fts.mjs:81-184\"]},\n18:     {\"id\":\"f-evidence-gap\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"No published generation, active profile, workload trace, full-corpus timing, or human relevance set exists.\",\"sources\":[\"013 research.md:38-44\",\"foundation implementation-summary.md:117-123\"]},\n19:     {\"id\":\"f-default-not-cleared\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Present evidence does not clear a threshold for permanent default-path ownership.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-003.md\"]},\n20:     {\"id\":\"f-score-shelf\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Weighted present-state score favors shelving 85/100 over wiring 54/100.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\"]},\n21:     {\"id\":\"f-formal-shelf\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Formal shelving removes the supported runtime surface rather than preserving undocumented dormant modes.\",\"sources\":[\"gap-analysis.md:168-171\",\"iteration-004.md\"]},\n22:     {\"id\":\"f-reactivation-gates\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Reactivation requires conjunctive evidence gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\",\"015 roadmap specs\"]},\n23:     {\"id\":\"f-blast-radius\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"Executable DB coupling outside the DB tree is isolated to the adapter, facade, and adapter tests.\",\"sources\":[\"scoped dependency Grep\"]},\n24:     {\"id\":\"f-wire-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A safe wire plan begins with distribution, measurement, refresh ownership, and shadow/relevance gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-005.md\"]},\n25:     {\"id\":\"f-shelf-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A formal shelf removes live DB modes/code and supersedes the roadmap while retaining the flat manifest and design evidence.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-005.md\"]}\n26:   ],\n27:   \"ruledOutDirections\": [\n28:     {\"approach\":\"Rewrite consumers for a database API\",\"reason\":\"The existing facade already isolates backend selection.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n29:     {\"approach\":\"Move authoritative content into SQLite\",\"reason\":\"Consumer hydration semantics rely on bounded flat artifacts.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n30:     {\"approach\":\"Flip the adapter default without publishing and owning the database lifecycle\",\"reason\":\"Clean checkouts have no generation pointer and reads correctly fail closed.\",\"iterations\":[2]},\n31:     {\"approach\":\"Use feature richness as proof of value\",\"reason\":\"Implemented supply does not establish observed consumer demand.\",\"iterations\":[2]},\n32:     {\"approach\":\"Promote based on the 20-style timing assertion\",\"reason\":\"It proves directionality but records no current-scale materiality.\",\"iterations\":[3]},\n33:     {\"approach\":\"Treat correctness coverage as product demand\",\"reason\":\"Safety evidence does not establish workload value.\",\"iterations\":[3]},\n34:     {\"approach\":\"Keep dormant modes indefinitely for optionality\",\"reason\":\"Git history preserves recovery without active maintenance ownership.\",\"iterations\":[4]},\n35:     {\"approach\":\"Promote from sunk cost or one benchmark\",\"reason\":\"Promotion requires all materiality, quality, and operational gates.\",\"iterations\":[4]},\n36:     {\"approach\":\"Leave DB switches live after shelving\",\"reason\":\"That preserves the current dormant ambiguity.\",\"iterations\":[5]},\n37:     {\"approach\":\"Lazy query-time database build\",\"reason\":\"Integrity-sensitive reads should not trigger corpus mutation.\",\"iterations\":[5]},\n38:     {\"approach\":\"Delete the flat retrieval manifest\",\"reason\":\"It is the canonical flat-engine freshness and generation guard.\",\"iterations\":[5]}\n39:   ],\n40:   \"metrics\": {\n41:     \"iterationsCompleted\": 5,\n42:     \"openQuestions\": 0,\n43:     \"resolvedQuestions\": 5,\n44:     \"keyFindings\": 15,\n45:     \"convergenceScore\": 0.0,\n46:     \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":16,\"spec\":7,\"tests\":5,\"measurement\":1}\n47:   },\n48:   \"status\": \"synthesizing\",\n49:   \"sessionId\": \"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\n50:   \"generation\": 1\n51: }\n\n(End of file - total 51 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"openQuestions\": [],\n  \"resolvedQuestions\": [\n    {\"id\":\"q-consumers\",\"text\":\"What contract and workload do the four design-mode corpus consumers require?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":1,\"answer\":\"A bounded generation-safe query/hydration facade; no consumer requires SQLite specifically.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"q-readiness\",\"text\":\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":2,\"answer\":\"Technically mature, but missing a published artifact and an owned build/distribution/refresh/repair lifecycle plus live cutover evidence.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"q-economics\",\"text\":\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":3,\"answer\":\"It credibly removes repeat-query corpus I/O, but current-scale materiality and demand are unmeasured while defaulting introduces permanent publication, freshness, migration, monitoring, and repair ownership.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"q-criteria\",\"text\":\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":4,\"answer\":\"A weighted current-fit/materiality/operations/integrity/future/reversibility framework favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100; reactivation requires all evidence gates.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"q-plans\",\"text\":\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":5,\"answer\":\"Wire only through distribution/build/refresh/shadow/relevance/cutover gates; shelf by removing live DB modes/code and superseding its roadmap while preserving flat-manifest safety and design evidence.\"}\n  ],\n  \"keyFindings\": [\n    {\"id\":\"f-consumer-facade\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"All four corpus modules use the storage-neutral runQuery/runHydrate facade.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:181-207\",\"four corpus modules\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-content-authority\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Flat artifacts remain authoritative content under persistent selection.\",\"sources\":[\"consumer hydration calls\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-legacy-freshness-cost\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Legacy queries rebuild and compare the live corpus manifest on every call.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:123-159\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-db-mature\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"The persistent projection and operator machinery are technically mature.\",\"sources\":[\"schema.mjs:35-269\",\"retrieval.mjs:364-510\",\"operator.mjs:75-247\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-lifecycle-unowned\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"No default build, distribution, refresh, or repair owner exists.\",\"sources\":[\"README.md:40-49\",\"operator.mjs:213-226\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-shadow-bounded\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Shadow parity tolerates ranking and identity differences and is not a sufficient cutover gate alone.\",\"sources\":[\"persistent-adapter.mjs:113-141\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-benefit-directional\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Persistent selection is directionally faster, but current-scale materiality is unmeasured.\",\"sources\":[\"adapter.test.mjs:107-132\",\"rank-fts.mjs:81-184\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-evidence-gap\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"No published generation, active profile, workload trace, full-corpus timing, or human relevance set exists.\",\"sources\":[\"013 research.md:38-44\",\"foundation implementation-summary.md:117-123\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-default-not-cleared\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Present evidence does not clear a threshold for permanent default-path ownership.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-003.md\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-score-shelf\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Weighted present-state score favors shelving 85/100 over wiring 54/100.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\"]},","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json","text":"{\n  \"openQuestions\": [],\n  \"resolvedQuestions\": [\n    {\"id\":\"q-consumers\",\"text\":\"What contract and workload do the four design-mode corpus consumers require?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":1,\"answer\":\"A bounded generation-safe query/hydration facade; no consumer requires SQLite specifically.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"q-readiness\",\"text\":\"How complete is the persistent implementation and what remains to make it default?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":2,\"answer\":\"Technically mature, but missing a published artifact and an owned build/distribution/refresh/repair lifecycle plus live cutover evidence.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"q-economics\",\"text\":\"What measurable benefits and recurring costs does SQLite introduce at current scale?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":3,\"answer\":\"It credibly removes repeat-query corpus I/O, but current-scale materiality and demand are unmeasured while defaulting introduces permanent publication, freshness, migration, monitoring, and repair ownership.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"q-criteria\",\"text\":\"Which decision criteria and thresholds govern keep versus shelve?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":4,\"answer\":\"A weighted current-fit/materiality/operations/integrity/future/reversibility framework favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100; reactivation requires all evidence gates.\"},\n    {\"id\":\"q-plans\",\"text\":\"What are the safe wiring and deprecation plans?\",\"status\":\"resolved\",\"resolvedAtIteration\":5,\"answer\":\"Wire only through distribution/build/refresh/shadow/relevance/cutover gates; shelf by removing live DB modes/code and superseding its roadmap while preserving flat-manifest safety and design evidence.\"}\n  ],\n  \"keyFindings\": [\n    {\"id\":\"f-consumer-facade\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"All four corpus modules use the storage-neutral runQuery/runHydrate facade.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:181-207\",\"four corpus modules\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-content-authority\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Flat artifacts remain authoritative content under persistent selection.\",\"sources\":[\"consumer hydration calls\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-legacy-freshness-cost\",\"iteration\":1,\"summary\":\"Legacy queries rebuild and compare the live corpus manifest on every call.\",\"sources\":[\"style-library.mjs:123-159\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-db-mature\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"The persistent projection and operator machinery are technically mature.\",\"sources\":[\"schema.mjs:35-269\",\"retrieval.mjs:364-510\",\"operator.mjs:75-247\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-lifecycle-unowned\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"No default build, distribution, refresh, or repair owner exists.\",\"sources\":[\"README.md:40-49\",\"operator.mjs:213-226\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-shadow-bounded\",\"iteration\":2,\"summary\":\"Shadow parity tolerates ranking and identity differences and is not a sufficient cutover gate alone.\",\"sources\":[\"persistent-adapter.mjs:113-141\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-benefit-directional\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Persistent selection is directionally faster, but current-scale materiality is unmeasured.\",\"sources\":[\"adapter.test.mjs:107-132\",\"rank-fts.mjs:81-184\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-evidence-gap\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"No published generation, active profile, workload trace, full-corpus timing, or human relevance set exists.\",\"sources\":[\"013 research.md:38-44\",\"foundation implementation-summary.md:117-123\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-default-not-cleared\",\"iteration\":3,\"summary\":\"Present evidence does not clear a threshold for permanent default-path ownership.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-003.md\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-score-shelf\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Weighted present-state score favors shelving 85/100 over wiring 54/100.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-formal-shelf\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Formal shelving removes the supported runtime surface rather than preserving undocumented dormant modes.\",\"sources\":[\"gap-analysis.md:168-171\",\"iteration-004.md\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-reactivation-gates\",\"iteration\":4,\"summary\":\"Reactivation requires conjunctive evidence gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-004.md\",\"015 roadmap specs\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-blast-radius\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"Executable DB coupling outside the DB tree is isolated to the adapter, facade, and adapter tests.\",\"sources\":[\"scoped dependency Grep\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-wire-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A safe wire plan begins with distribution, measurement, refresh ownership, and shadow/relevance gates.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-005.md\"]},\n    {\"id\":\"f-shelf-plan\",\"iteration\":5,\"summary\":\"A formal shelf removes live DB modes/code and supersedes the roadmap while retaining the flat manifest and design evidence.\",\"sources\":[\"iteration-005.md\"]}\n  ],\n  \"ruledOutDirections\": [\n    {\"approach\":\"Rewrite consumers for a database API\",\"reason\":\"The existing facade already isolates backend selection.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n    {\"approach\":\"Move authoritative content into SQLite\",\"reason\":\"Consumer hydration semantics rely on bounded flat artifacts.\",\"iterations\":[1]},\n    {\"approach\":\"Flip the adapter default without publishing and owning the database lifecycle\",\"reason\":\"Clean checkouts have no generation pointer and reads correctly fail closed.\",\"iterations\":[2]},\n    {\"approach\":\"Use feature richness as proof of value\",\"reason\":\"Implemented supply does not establish observed consumer demand.\",\"iterations\":[2]},\n    {\"approach\":\"Promote based on the 20-style timing assertion\",\"reason\":\"It proves directionality but records no current-scale materiality.\",\"iterations\":[3]},\n    {\"approach\":\"Treat correctness coverage as product demand\",\"reason\":\"Safety evidence does not establish workload value.\",\"iterations\":[3]},\n    {\"approach\":\"Keep dormant modes indefinitely for optionality\",\"reason\":\"Git history preserves recovery without active maintenance ownership.\",\"iterations\":[4]},\n    {\"approach\":\"Promote from sunk cost or one benchmark\",\"reason\":\"Promotion requires all materiality, quality, and operational gates.\",\"iterations\":[4]},\n    {\"approach\":\"Leave DB switches live after shelving\",\"reason\":\"That preserves the current dormant ambiguity.\",\"iterations\":[5]},\n    {\"approach\":\"Lazy query-time database build\",\"reason\":\"Integrity-sensitive reads should not trigger corpus mutation.\",\"iterations\":[5]},\n    {\"approach\":\"Delete the flat retrieval manifest\",\"reason\":\"It is the canonical flat-engine freshness and generation guard.\",\"iterations\":[5]}\n  ],\n  \"metrics\": {\n    \"iterationsCompleted\": 5,\n    \"openQuestions\": 0,\n    \"resolvedQuestions\": 5,\n    \"keyFindings\": 15,\n    \"convergenceScore\": 0.0,\n    \"coverageBySources\": {\"code\":16,\"spec\":7,\"tests\":5,\"measurement\":1}\n  },\n  \"status\": \"synthesizing\",\n  \"sessionId\": \"fanout-sol-high-fast-1784622756165-kgdopz\",\n  \"generation\": 1\n}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":51,"totalLines":51,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/findings-registry.json","time":{"start":1784623663441,"end":1784623663467}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0214130f072a5df6016a5f322f03e0819186f75fd077f44932"}},"id":"prt_f83dc094b001V3sIC6zRSJHw9a","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","messageID":"msg_f83dbb4c8001mzy7FKcjG5lS24"}}
