{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784623663500,"sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_yLSuYnbBI4irDQLMsKXfMTHp","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Styles SQLite Database Fate: Progressive Research\n2: \n3: ## Current Direction\n4: \n5: The decision should preserve the existing storage-neutral consumer facade. The four design modes require bounded generation-safe selection and flat-file hydration, not SQLite itself. [SOURCE: iteration-001.md]\n6: \n7: The database is a mature rebuildable projection, but not a complete product integration. Safe defaulting requires an initial publication, a corpus-refresh owner, artifact/bootstrap policy, monitoring and repair, and stronger live cutover gates. [SOURCE: iteration-002.md]\n8: \n9: ## Evidence Accumulated\n10: \n11: - All consumer modules use `runQuery`/`runHydrate` through `style-library.mjs`.\n12: - Flat artifacts remain authoritative content under either backend.\n13: - Legacy retrieval rebuilds and compares the live manifest on each query, creating the clearest potential benefit for a persistent index.\n14: - Persistent retrieval supplies FTS5, vectors, RRF, cursors, attribution, immutable generations, rollback, telemetry, and an operator surface.\n15: - Query/hydrate never auto-build; clean checkouts have no published generation.\n16: - Shadow mode is a migration aid, not a complete relevance or strict ranking proof.\n17: \n18: ## Open Decision\n19: \n20: Whether that avoidable per-query work and future retrieval capabilities outweigh build/publication/repair complexity at a 1,290-style corpus.\n21: \n22: ## Evidence Quality\n23: \n24: The economic evidence does not presently support defaulting. Legacy retrieval performs substantial repeated I/O, and persistent mode is directionally faster, but only a synthetic 20-style assertion exists. There is no published full-corpus generation, workload trace, current-scale p50/p95, active vector profile, or human relevance set. Correctness is well proven; material value is not. [SOURCE: iteration-003.md]\n25: \n26: ## Provisional Verdict\n27: \n28: Favor formal shelving as the current default decision, with objective reactivation gates. This avoids turning an unmeasured projection into a permanent operational dependency while preserving a path to promote it if real workload evidence clears the bar.\n29: \n30: ## Decision Framework\n31: \n32: Weighted present-state scoring favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100 across current consumer fit, measured material value, operational ownership, integrity/rollback, future leverage, and reversibility. The database wins integrity and future leverage; shelving wins the higher-weight present-use and ownership criteria. [SOURCE: iteration-004.md]\n33: \n34: Reactivation requires all of: a representative workload; approved SLO breach or >=30% and >=25 ms p95 improvement; measured full-corpus build/size; owned deterministic refresh/distribution; strict facade/generation/refusal parity; no material human-judged relevance regression; successful shadow and rollback; and demonstrated persistent-only demand or latency need.\n35: \n36: ## Execution Plans\n37: \n38: The kept path must prove clean-checkout distribution, build and refresh ownership, full-corpus measurements, strict shadow/oracle/relevance parity, and rollback before changing the default. The shelved path removes DB-only runtime code and mode surfaces, routes the facade directly to the flat engine, retains the flat retrieval manifest, marks the 015 roadmap superseded, and verifies all engine plus corpus suites. [SOURCE: iteration-005.md]\n\n(End of file - total 38 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Styles SQLite Database Fate: Progressive Research\n\n## Current Direction\n\nThe decision should preserve the existing storage-neutral consumer facade. The four design modes require bounded generation-safe selection and flat-file hydration, not SQLite itself. [SOURCE: iteration-001.md]\n\nThe database is a mature rebuildable projection, but not a complete product integration. Safe defaulting requires an initial publication, a corpus-refresh owner, artifact/bootstrap policy, monitoring and repair, and stronger live cutover gates. [SOURCE: iteration-002.md]\n\n## Evidence Accumulated\n\n- All consumer modules use `runQuery`/`runHydrate` through `style-library.mjs`.\n- Flat artifacts remain authoritative content under either backend.\n- Legacy retrieval rebuilds and compares the live manifest on each query, creating the clearest potential benefit for a persistent index.\n- Persistent retrieval supplies FTS5, vectors, RRF, cursors, attribution, immutable generations, rollback, telemetry, and an operator surface.\n- Query/hydrate never auto-build; clean checkouts have no published generation.\n- Shadow mode is a migration aid, not a complete relevance or strict ranking proof.\n\n## Open Decision\n\nWhether that avoidable per-query work and future retrieval capabilities outweigh build/publication/repair complexity at a 1,290-style corpus.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0093-sk-design-012-gap-research/.opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md","text":"# Styles SQLite Database Fate: Progressive Research\n\n## Current Direction\n\nThe decision should preserve the existing storage-neutral consumer facade. The four design modes require bounded generation-safe selection and flat-file hydration, not SQLite itself. [SOURCE: iteration-001.md]\n\nThe database is a mature rebuildable projection, but not a complete product integration. Safe defaulting requires an initial publication, a corpus-refresh owner, artifact/bootstrap policy, monitoring and repair, and stronger live cutover gates. [SOURCE: iteration-002.md]\n\n## Evidence Accumulated\n\n- All consumer modules use `runQuery`/`runHydrate` through `style-library.mjs`.\n- Flat artifacts remain authoritative content under either backend.\n- Legacy retrieval rebuilds and compares the live manifest on each query, creating the clearest potential benefit for a persistent index.\n- Persistent retrieval supplies FTS5, vectors, RRF, cursors, attribution, immutable generations, rollback, telemetry, and an operator surface.\n- Query/hydrate never auto-build; clean checkouts have no published generation.\n- Shadow mode is a migration aid, not a complete relevance or strict ranking proof.\n\n## Open Decision\n\nWhether that avoidable per-query work and future retrieval capabilities outweigh build/publication/repair complexity at a 1,290-style corpus.\n\n## Evidence Quality\n\nThe economic evidence does not presently support defaulting. Legacy retrieval performs substantial repeated I/O, and persistent mode is directionally faster, but only a synthetic 20-style assertion exists. There is no published full-corpus generation, workload trace, current-scale p50/p95, active vector profile, or human relevance set. Correctness is well proven; material value is not. [SOURCE: iteration-003.md]\n\n## Provisional Verdict\n\nFavor formal shelving as the current default decision, with objective reactivation gates. This avoids turning an unmeasured projection into a permanent operational dependency while preserving a path to promote it if real workload evidence clears the bar.\n\n## Decision Framework\n\nWeighted present-state scoring favors shelf 85/100 over wire 54/100 across current consumer fit, measured material value, operational ownership, integrity/rollback, future leverage, and reversibility. The database wins integrity and future leverage; shelving wins the higher-weight present-use and ownership criteria. [SOURCE: iteration-004.md]\n\nReactivation requires all of: a representative workload; approved SLO breach or >=30% and >=25 ms p95 improvement; measured full-corpus build/size; owned deterministic refresh/distribution; strict facade/generation/refusal parity; no material human-judged relevance regression; successful shadow and rollback; and demonstrated persistent-only demand or latency need.\n\n## Execution Plans\n\nThe kept path must prove clean-checkout distribution, build and refresh ownership, full-corpus measurements, strict shadow/oracle/relevance parity, and rollback before changing the default. The shelved path removes DB-only runtime code and mode surfaces, routes the facade directly to the flat engine, retains the flat retrieval manifest, marks the 015 roadmap superseded, and verifies all engine plus corpus suites. [SOURCE: iteration-005.md]","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":38,"totalLines":38,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/012-style-database-and-interface-commands/007-gap-remediation-research/003-db-fate/research/lineages/sol-high-fast/research.md","time":{"start":1784623663471,"end":1784623663496}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0214130f072a5df6016a5f322f03ec8191b74bf2b0c9bfa20f"}},"id":"prt_f83dc0956001Hup4W5GAyew2vt","sessionID":"ses_07c31cbc4ffeYIOJJ8ZhDDe6Fl","messageID":"msg_f83dbb4c8001mzy7FKcjG5lS24"}}
